							<!-- Section Content-->

							<p>The year 2020 began with high hopes and expectations, not only because it was a new year but also a new decade. People all over the world had great optimism, thinking that something new and exciting was coming. However, little did anyone know that a new disease discovered in China would quickly spread worldwide, turning the year into a global pandemic.</p>

							<p>For those in the prepping and survival community, COVID-19 is considered a TEOTWAWKI event. This stands for &ldquo;The End of the World as We Know it.&rdquo; However, this doesn&#39;t mean that the world has come to an end, but rather that the world we now live in is different from the one we knew before. The pandemic has caused nationwide lockdowns, businesses to shut down, and people to stay at home, something that would have been unimaginable in the past.</p>

							<p>The old normal is no more, and people are now searching for the &quot;new normal.&quot; Will wearing masks and social distancing become a part of everyday life? Will more people work from home, and will online shopping replace brick-and-mortar stores? Will homeschooling become more common than traditional public schools?</p>

							<p>These and many other questions define this new normal. It&#39;s not just up to one person or committee to answer them, but it&#39;s about how society adapts to the situation that COVID-19 has created. However, one thing is certain, and that is that the world has already changed, and it will continue to change in the future.</p>

							<p>The COVID-19 pandemic has brought about a sudden realization among the general population of the importance of survival preparedness. The group known as &ldquo;preppers&rdquo; used to be viewed as paranoid and fringe, but now they are seen as the most forward-thinking individuals on the planet. People who once laughed at the idea of preppers are now waiting in long lines at grocery stores, hoping to buy food, water, cleaning supplies, and toilet paper to build their own stockpiles.</p>

							<p>The pandemic has caused a global shortage of critical personal protective equipment such as medical masks and gloves. Retailers have set their stocks aside for medical personnel, who need them the most, leaving the general population without adequate protection. However, shortages have not been limited to PPE, as grocery store shelves have become bare of certain categories of food, medical and cleaning supplies, and even toilet paper. The shortage of toilet paper, in particular, has left many people wondering how it could have happened.</p>

							<p>As the pandemic continues, people are realizing that they need to be more self-sufficient and prepared for emergencies. The ability to provide for oneself and one&#39;s family during times of crisis is no longer considered paranoid or extreme. It has become a necessity. The importance of having a well-stocked pantry, a supply of clean water, and other essential items is now apparent to all. The pandemic has shown that disasters can strike at any time and that everyone needs to be prepared to face them.</p>

							<p>The importance of emergency preparedness has been highlighted by the Coronavirus pandemic. This is a need that modern society has largely lost, even though our ancestors through the centuries lived that way. If we go back a century, agriculture wasn&#39;t the industrialized version we have today. Rather, it was small family-owned and operated farms. The crops that were planted every year were hoped to be harvested before the first fall freeze so that there would be food to survive the winter. Without a good harvest, survival was questionable. We have become far removed from that in modern society and often don&#39;t even recognize where the things we need come from.</p>

							<p>The pandemic has forced people to recognize the importance of emergency preparedness. Modern society has largely lost this need, and we have become far removed from our agricultural roots. A century ago, small family-owned and operated farms grew foodstuffs to feed their local population. In those times, a good harvest was critical to survival. Unfortunately, people have become complacent and don&#39;t realize where the things they need come from. There are even those who believe that meat comes from the grocery store without any animals being killed to produce it. However, if the grocery stores and restaurants suddenly shut down, they wouldn&#39;t have any idea where to come up with food to eat.</p>

							<p>The society we live in has insulated us from the basic necessities of survival, but that does not mean that those necessities will always be available. Despite our sophisticated technology, we cannot control the weather or guarantee the availability of resources. The COVID-19 pandemic exposed the fragility of our supply chains. A mere scare of the disease was enough to empty grocery store shelves and meat departments. As many meatpacking plants shut down due to the disease, it is yet to be seen if there will be a second run on meat.</p>

							<p>Life is fragile, and the systems we put in place to protect ourselves are fragile too. The tsunami that hit northeastern Japan in 2011 and Hurricane Harvey that flooded Houston in 2017 are examples of how quickly disasters can destroy entire cities and displace thousands of people. Polite society may appear civilized, but that does not make the world itself civilized or guarantee that everyone in the world is civilized. There are still people who are ready to take advantage of disasters to prey on their fellow humans.</p>

							<p>Despite our modern advancements, we must remember that our ancestors understood the importance of being prepared for emergencies. They lived in small, family-owned farms and grew foodstuffs to feed their local populations. Farmers planted their crops each year, hoping to get them in before the first fall freeze, so that there would be enough food to survive the winter. Today, many people do not even know where their food comes from, and some even believe that meat comes from the grocery store without any animals being killed.</p>

							<p>The COVID-19 pandemic has raised awareness of the need to be prepared for emergencies, but it should not take a crisis for us to recognize the fragility of life and the world we live in. We cannot control everything, but we can take steps to be ready for disasters and ensure that we have the basic necessities of survival.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>WHY IS IT IMPORTANT TO BE PREPARED</strong></p>

							<p>When it comes to the question of &ldquo;Why is it important to be prepared?&rdquo; some might wonder why it&rsquo;s necessary to do so. However, given the many dangers present in the world, it&rsquo;s almost incredulous not to prepare for disasters. But, for the sake of argument, let&rsquo;s answer their question.</p>

							<p>No matter where you live in the world, there is danger present. Even if we exclude the danger caused by criminals and other unsavory characters, there&rsquo;s always the risk of natural disasters. Perhaps you don&rsquo;t live in an area that&rsquo;s prone to hurricanes, but there are probably tornadoes, earthquakes, or winter blizzards to worry about. Just because you don&rsquo;t face the same kind of danger that someone else does, it doesn&rsquo;t mean that you&rsquo;re immune to disasters.</p>

							<p>Statistically speaking, the average person will go through some type of disaster every eight years, whether it&rsquo;s a natural disaster, a regional disaster, a financial disaster, or a personal disaster. That means that each of us could face anywhere from five to ten disasters in our lifetime.</p>

							<p>Most of us simply try to make do as best we can during disasters, suffering through them as they come. In some cases, government bailouts and non-profit organizations can offer aid. But regardless of the help available, those who are living through the disaster suffer loss - often much more than they can hope to regain.</p>

							<p>The idea of FEMA bailing out people in the event of a disaster is a misguided one. The agency has a poor track record, as evidenced by their performance during Hurricane Katrina and Hurricane Sandy. Even some cities have turned down FEMA&#39;s offer of help due to their bad reputation. Furthermore, government aid is often hindered by red tape, which slows down the assistance and can have strings attached to it that may result in future payments.</p>

							<p>Additionally, FEMA is not able to provide help quickly enough. The agency advises people to have at least three days&#39; worth of food and water on-hand because they are supposed to have relief in place within 72 hours. However, they often fail to meet that goal. During Hurricane Sandy, they did not even start putting out RFQs (request for quotes) until the day after the hurricane had already hit the New Jersey seashore. This delay can make a huge difference when it comes to saving lives and providing assistance to those in need.</p>

							<p>Given these limitations, it&#39;s clear that relying solely on FEMA is not a viable disaster preparedness plan. Instead, individuals should take responsibility for their own preparedness by stockpiling food, water, and other supplies to last for several days or even weeks. Being self-sufficient during a disaster can not only save lives but can also ease the burden on emergency responders and relief agencies. In short, it&#39;s essential to prepare for disasters rather than relying on outside help that may not come quickly or at all.</p>

							<p>It is important to note that relying on the government to rescue you during emergencies is a relatively recent concept. In fact, FEMA wasn&#39;t established until 1979. Prior to that, individuals were responsible for taking care of themselves and relied on assistance from their communities, such as friends, neighbors, and religious organizations. However, the government, along with other governments worldwide, is making significant efforts to discourage this independent mindset.</p>

							<p>Prepping is about taking control of your life and ensuring your safety during emergencies, rather than relying on the government for assistance. This may seem like a foreign concept in today&#39;s society, but it has been a successful approach for centuries. While some may not have survived, they did not put others at risk to take care of them.</p>

							<p>Deciding how much to prepare is a personal decision, and there are no strict guidelines that must be followed. Some people may suggest certain amounts of food or ammunition, but ultimately, you must decide what works best for you.</p>

							<p>Initially, the idea of prepping may seem overwhelming. There are many tasks to be done, and it can be challenging to know where to start. However, everyone&#39;s preparedness journey is unique, and there is no one-size-fits-all solution. It&#39;s important to remember that you don&#39;t have to do everything at once, and some things that work for others may not be practical for you.</p>

							<p>Rather than being intimidated, approach prepping as a journey rather than a destination. Every step you take towards preparedness will improve your chances of survival and provide increased security for you and your family. By taking small steps towards preparedness, you&#39;ll feel more in control and confident in your ability to handle any emergency.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>FACING THE RISK</strong></p>

							<p>We all live in a world full of risks, and this reality has existed for as long as humans have. Although the specific risks we face may vary, there are still many that affect us all. The degree to which these risks affect us can also differ depending on our particular situation. It&#39;s essential to ask what these risks are, how severe they are, and how likely they are to happen, so we can make informed decisions about how to prepare for them.</p>

							<p>Breaking it down and analyzing these risks is crucial. It allows us to assess the potential impact of each one and decide which ones are most significant to our lives. This knowledge helps us to identify the appropriate steps to take to protect ourselves and our loved ones. So, it&#39;s important to educate ourselves about the risks and be prepared to face them.</p>

							<p><strong>COPING WITH PERSONAL DISASTERS</strong></p>

							<p>Encountering personal disasters is a universal experience. These are events that impact only us or our family members. They are the most frequent type of disasters that we may encounter, making up more than half of the potential crises we may face in our lives. Personal disasters encompass a variety of events, including the following:</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Loss of a job</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Loss of a loved one</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Divorce</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Major accident or illness</li>
							</ul>

							<p>Every personal disaster has an emotional and financial or material aspect. While none of them may qualify as a survival situation, they can be serious enough to cause significant disruptions to our families, particularly if the financial repercussions result in the loss of our home.</p>

							<p>When planning for these scenarios, minimizing the financial impact is critical. We can&#39;t do much to alleviate the emotional impact of losing a loved one, but we can control the expenses associated with the funeral. Decreasing the financial impact not only provides stability and security for our families, but it also lessens the overall emotional impact by avoiding additional stress and problems in addition to the original disaster.</p>

							<p><strong>COPING WITH NATURAL DISASTERS</strong></p>

							<p>No matter where you reside in the world, natural disasters can strike at any moment. The real question is not whether you will face disasters, but rather what type of disasters you will encounter and how severe they will be. You may assume that your area is safe from disasters, but you may be forgetting to account for severe weather events. Disasters can include hurricanes, tornadoes, forest fires, earthquakes, winter blizzards, thunderstorms, flooding, and tsunamis. These disasters all have emotional and financial implications, but they also include a survival aspect. Each year, people lose their lives to these disasters. But surviving the disaster is only part of the challenge. The aftermath of the disaster is often more difficult to navigate, especially when trying to meet your family&#39;s needs while salvaging and rebuilding your home.</p>

							<p>The good news is that natural disasters usually bring a wave of aid through individuals and non-profit organizations. People provide food, clothing, water, building materials, and even aid in rebuilding your home. However, it is mostly up to you to keep your family alive during the recovery period when life is far from normal. Prepping is more about surviving the aftermath of a disaster than the disaster itself. For instance, a hurricane might last for a day or two, but the time it takes to recover and return to normalcy can take weeks or even months. Without the ability to work during that period or without electricity, you may face difficulties feeding your family and keeping them warm.</p>

							<p><strong>COPING WITH MAJOR DISASTERS</strong></p>

							<p>A disaster that affects a large region is considered a major disaster, and it can be challenging to deal with due to the widespread impact. In such situations, resources are often insufficient to help everyone, and non-profit organizations may find themselves short of funds. Some examples of major disasters include pandemics, financial collapses, events that take down the electrical grid, asteroid impacts, and zombie apocalypses. While governments may attempt to provide aid on a national scale, there can be repercussions such as adding to the national debt. Any of these disasters could lead to a TEOTWAWKI (The End Of The World As We Know It) scenario, requiring long-term survival skills. For example, an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) attack could potentially take down the US electrical grid and cause widespread deaths from starvation and disease. In such a case, being self-sufficient in terms of food, water, and firewood would be crucial for survival.</p>

							<p><strong>EVALUATING RISKS</strong></p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><img src="{{asset('assets/img/image/evaluating_risk.png')}}" style="height:300px; width:626px" /></p>

							<p>When it comes to potential disasters, some can be more problematic than others due to their severity of impact, while others can pose a greater risk due to their likelihood of occurrence. As such, it&#39;s important to assess which disasters should be given priority. This can be achieved by creating a risk matrix that evaluates the likelihood and impact of each potential disaster.</p>

							<p>The risk matrix is a chart with two axes labeled &quot;likelihood&quot; and &quot;impact.&quot; Each potential disaster is rated for both of these factors and placed in the appropriate box on the chart. After evaluating each potential disaster, we can add up the scores for likelihood and impact to determine a total risk score for each item.</p>

							<p>It&#39;s important to note that the examples given may not be an exhaustive list of potential disasters. The scores for each potential disaster listed in the chart are as follows: EMP - 9, Hurricane - 8, Sickness - 6, Loss of Job - 6, Zombies - 6, Blizzard - 5, Invasion - 5, Death - 4, Pandemic - 4, Blackout - 2.</p>

							<p>By using a risk matrix to evaluate potential disasters, we can better understand which ones pose the greatest risks to us and prepare accordingly.</p>

							<p>The listed disasters have been ordered in descending order, from the highest score to the lowest. The top two disasters in the example are EMP and Hurricane, with EMP having the highest score, followed by Hurricane. It is interesting to note that Hurricane is considered more likely to occur, while the impact of an EMP is believed to be greater.</p>

							<p>While it is important not to overlook any potential disaster on the list (excluding a zombie apocalypse), the focus of our preparedness efforts should be on the disasters with the highest scores, such as an EMP or a hurricane. By doing so, we increase our chances of being prepared for the disasters that we are most likely to encounter.</p>

							<p>An EMP is an excellent disaster to use as a framework for long-term preparedness because it covers almost anything by bringing down our entire infrastructure and supply chain through the electrical grid. However, preparing for an EMP does not necessarily mean that we will be prepared for everything. There are specific requirements for a pandemic that are not covered in an EMP preparedness plan.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>PART 1 - HOW TO START</strong></p>

							<p>If you&#39;re new to prepping and reading this book, you&#39;ll likely want to make progress as quickly as possible. This desire is common among those whom I&#39;ve helped. In this section, we&#39;ll cover the basics of what you need to have and do in order to survive. We&#39;ll also discuss the first steps you should take to acquire the necessary equipment and supplies. By completing the tasks outlined in this section, you&#39;ll be ahead of 99% of the population, even those who stockpiled for COVID-19.</p>

							<p>A common issue with people who only stock up for a particular disaster is that they relax and return to normal once the disaster is over. The items they purchased to get through the disaster are used for everyday purposes, and when faced with another potential disaster, they must start all over again. We won&#39;t operate that way. Instead, we&#39;ll gather equipment and build a stockpile that we&#39;ll maintain. This doesn&#39;t mean that we&#39;ll never use the food or other items we purchase, but rather that we&#39;ll replace them if we use them.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>WHAT YOU NEED TO FOCUS ON WHEN TALKING ABOUT SURVIVAL</strong></p>

							<p>The average teenager may believe that their survival priorities include their smartphone and a latte, but they have a very different idea of what survival truly entails. Many people are unaware of what is essential to keep them alive, as opposed to what makes them happy. It&#39;s important to understand this distinction when discussing survival priorities.</p>

							<p>Survival priorities refer to those items that are necessary to sustain life. The length of time that our bodies can survive without these specific items is a crucial factor. While your teenage daughter may argue that she cannot live without her phone, in reality, she could survive for several years without it. This is something I know from personal experience, having lived over 30 years without one.</p>

							<p>It&#39;s essential to prioritize our true survival needs over what we may consider to be important for our daily happiness. Understanding this distinction can make all the difference in a true survival situation. So, while a latte may provide temporary pleasure, it is not a survival priority. It&#39;s important to focus on the essentials to ensure our survival in any situation.</p>

							<p>Conversely, there are certain necessities such as water and food that are vital for survival and cannot be overlooked. These are the critical items that we need to consider when preparing for emergency situations. As a result, our top four survival priorities are based on these fundamental requirements.</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Oxygen, which we can only live without for about three minutes.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Maintaining our core body heat, which we can only live without for about 30 minutes.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Clean drinking water, which we can only live without for about three days.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Food, which we can only live without for about 30 days.</li>
							</ul>

							

							<p>Upon examination of these numbers, it becomes apparent that they all consist of the digit 3. This concept is referred to as the rule of threes and serves as a helpful tool to recall the top survival priorities and their degree of importance. While the figures may not be precise, they are sufficiently accurate for our purposes. Survival essentially means providing our bodies with these essential necessities. However, oxygen is beyond our control - we either have it or we don&#39;t. If, for example, the planet&#39;s oxygen supply were to suddenly vanish, it would render the other priorities irrelevant; none of us would survive. Despite being our primary survival priorities, they are not the sole factors to consider when discussing survival. There are three additional critical areas that, while not categorized as survival priorities in the same sense, are significant enough that neglecting them could potentially result in fatal consequences. These supplementary priorities are:</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Starting a fire &ndash; necessary for warmth, cooking food, and purifying water</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">First-aid &ndash; critical for treating injuries and preventing infections to maintain good health</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Self-defense &ndash; important to protect yourself, family, and resources in case of threats or attacks</li>
							</ul>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>ENSURING AN ADEQUATE SUPPLY OF CLEAN DRINKING WATER</strong></p>

							<p>It&#39;s easy to take for granted the abundance of clean water available with a simple turn of a faucet. However, we must remember that without sufficient clean drinking water, we will die quickly. Health experts recommend drinking eight, eight-ounce glasses of water per day, which aligns with the standard survival wisdom of one gallon of clean water per person per day for drinking and cooking.</p>

							<p>However, those who work in the hot sun or engage in physical activity may need considerably more water, as they can quickly sweat out more than a gallon per day. Additionally, water is required for other purposes, such as bathing, washing clothes, and watering vegetable gardens. Although the rest of the water does not have to be biologically clean like the water we drink, it can still be used as grey water.</p>

							<p>Clean water refers to water that is free of bacteria, viruses, and protozoa, which cause dysentery and disease. Grey water is used water that is repurposed for other uses, such as watering gardens. In a survival situation, we cannot trust any water source. We must assume that all water is contaminated, including the water from our kitchen faucet, unless we have been explicitly informed by our municipal water authority that it is safe to drink. Flooding and hurricanes can compromise city water systems, and city water may stop flowing, especially if the electrical grid goes down. Therefore, we must have an alternative water source that we can use in case of an emergency.</p>

							

							<p><strong>Where to Locate Water Sources in an Urban Environment</strong></p>

							<p>Having access to multiple sources of water is crucial for survival, considering the significance of water as a top priority. Depending on a single source of water can pose a risk, as it may not be sufficient to fulfill the needs of everyone who requires it. Additionally, some groups may try to claim and control the water source, making it unavailable to others. Therefore, the ideal option is to collect water on your own. This can be achieved by:</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Well: Drilling a well may require a permit and is expensive, but it&#39;s the most reliable source of water. Make sure to have a manual pump or solar panels to power the pump.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Rainwater harvesting: Simply add rain barrels under gutters and downspouts to collect rainwater.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Humidity catchers: Works in high humidity areas with enough wind, extract water directly from the air.</li>
							</ul>

							

							<p>It is important to note that even though the water from these sources may seem clean, it still needs to be purified. Rainwater may contain bird droppings as it falls on your roof. In addition to the sources already mentioned, there are usually other water sources in our surroundings that we may not be aware of. Some of these sources may be indicated on a topographical map, which can be found at<a href="http://www.usgs.gov/" style="text-decoration:none"> <span style="color:#1155cc"><u>www.usgs.gov</u></a>. However, it is essential not to limit yourself to this resource alone. Take the time to explore your neighborhood carefully and discover any hidden water sources that may be available to use in a post-disaster scenario. Make sure to mark them on a map with a descriptive legend and keep it in your survival notebook. Look for: Lakes and ponds, Rivers and streams, Canals, Public swimming pools, Public fountains, Large, multi-floor commercial buildings, and Water towers.</p>

							

							<p>To collect and transport the water you find, it&#39;s important to have a method that doesn&#39;t rely on your car. A hand cart, wagon, or hand truck can be used with five-gallon buckets or jugs. Additionally, you&#39;ll need a faucet bib key to access water from commercial buildings and the testing port on water towers.</p>

							<p><strong>How to Purify Your Water</strong></p>

							<p>Ensuring the purity of the water you drink is crucial, no matter the source. With various methods available, it&#39;s recommended to have at least two or more purification options readily accessible.</p>

							<p><strong>Talking About Filtration</strong></p>

							<p>Water treatment plants utilize filtration as well as chemical purification to ensure the safety of drinking water. However, relying solely on filtration to purify water requires a high-quality filtration system. Regular &quot;whole house filters&quot; that eliminate sediment from water are insufficient as they only filter down to 10 microns, while bacteria can range from 0.2 to 2.0 microns, and viruses are even smaller, ranging from 20 to 400 nanometers or 0.02 to 0.4 microns in size.</p>

							<p>Fortunately, there are several excellent filters available in the market specifically designed for the survival community, capable of filtering out 99.99% of bacteria and some viruses. It is essential to carefully review the specifications of any filter you plan to purchase to ensure that it meets your requirements.</p>

							<p>However, filtration as a method of purifying water has a disadvantage in that most filters eventually become clogged. If the filter cartridge cannot be backflushed, it will need to be replaced periodically. Nonetheless, not all filter cartridges are created equal. Some filters can last significantly longer, measured in the number of gallons they purify, than others. Surprisingly, some of the most expensive filter elements can be the most economical to use due to the number of gallons of water they can filter before becoming clogged.</p>

							<p><strong>Talking About Chemical Purification</strong></p>

							<p>Chemical purification is a method of water treatment that involves adding chemicals to the water to kill microorganisms. Chlorine is the most commonly used chemical in water treatment and is used in almost all municipal water processing plants as well as swimming pools. Iodine is also a viable option, but it is more expensive.</p>

							<p>You can easily find chlorine in swimming pool chemicals or in bleach, which is used to whiten clothes. However, it is important to note that you should avoid buying the color safe or scented kinds of bleach. Instead, purchase normal bleach, which has a chlorine content of 5.25% or 6.0%.</p>

							<p>To purify water using chlorine bleach, add eight drops of bleach to a gallon of water and stir. Allow the water to sit for 20 minutes before drinking. If you don&#39;t like the smell of chlorine, let the purified water sit overnight to allow the chlorine to evaporate.</p>

							<p>For larger quantities of water, you can measure the chlorine bleach in cubic centimeters or milliliters. One milliliter is equivalent to 20 drops of bleach, so a five-gallon bucket requires 2 ml of bleach and a 55-gallon drum requires 22 ml of bleach. It is recommended that you treat all stored water in your stockpile to keep it fresh and pure.</p>

							<p><strong>Talking About Heat Purification</strong></p>

							<p>Water can be purified by boiling it, but it is not necessary to bring it to 212&deg;F (100&deg;C). Instead, water can be pasteurized by heating it to 162&deg;F (72&deg;C) for 15 seconds. There is a device called a WAPI (Water Pasteurization Indicator) that can be used to pasteurize water in third-world countries. The WAPI is a plastic capsule with a wax bead inside it that melts at 160&deg;F, indicating that the water is pasteurized. Once removed from the hot water, the wax solidifies, making it possible to reuse the WAPI again and again.</p>

							<p>The best option for heat purification is to make a still. Stills work by bringing the water to the boiling point, so that liquid water turns into steam. The water vapor is then run through a condenser, typically made of copper tubing, where it will cool and return to a liquid state. In this process, everything besides the water gets left behind, including chemicals, minerals, bacteria, salt, and other dissolved solids that do not turn to a vapor at 212&deg;F (100&deg;C).</p>

							<p>Using a still is the only way to convert ocean water to drinkable water. If you live near the seashore, you could have an endless supply of drinkable water in the worst survival situations if you have a still to purify it.</p>

							<p><strong>Building a Water Stockpile for Emergency Situations</strong></p>

							<p>Stockpiling water is essential for surviving disasters, as it may be difficult to find water during an emergency. However, storing enough water for an extended period can be challenging due to space and purity issues. While most homes lack enough storage space, using 55-gallon drums can save space and cost, especially if stored in a basement.</p>

							<p>Blue plastic drums are commonly used for water storage, but they are chemical drums, and their contents may be harmful to human health. To use these drums safely, you must know what was in them previously, and if they contain any poisonous chemicals. Alternatively, white plastic drums are food-grade and require cleaning to remove any food residue. To clean the barrels, use a mixture of water with eight drops of bleach per gallon, let it sit for a minute, and then dump it out. Refill the barrels with water containing eight drops of bleach per gallon to prevent any growth of bacteria.</p>

							<p>For larger water storage, an above-ground swimming pool can be used. The chlorine required for swimming pools can purify the water, making it safe for drinking. A 12-foot diameter pool, 30 inches deep, can hold over 2,000 gallons of water, while a 16-foot diameter pool, 36 inches deep, can hold just over 4,500 gallons. Pools offer a significant advantage over smaller drums as they can store larger amounts of water, but also do not draw attention to the real purpose of the pool.</p>

							<p>In summary, while stockpiling water for extended periods is challenging, it is crucial to prepare for a disaster, as it can be challenging to find water during emergencies. Storing water in 55-gallon drums or above-ground pools is ideal, but it is essential to ensure the purity of the water by cleaning and using chlorine bleach.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>HOW TO PREPARE FOR EMERGENCIES AND DISASTERS</strong></p>

							<p>Proper food storage and supply is a critical component of emergency preparedness. While water is the most essential resource for survival, food is also vital for our body&#39;s sustenance. Without proper nutrition, our bodies can weaken, making it harder to perform necessary survival tasks and increasing susceptibility to diseases.</p>

							<p>On average, an American adult consumes around a ton of food per year, including meals cooked at home and restaurants. However, most people do not consume a healthy diet or the recommended 2,000 calories per day. Many of us can exceed this limit by lunchtime, and some fast-food chains offer supersized meals containing more than 2,000 calories.</p>

							<p>Nutritionists argue that our diet should include micronutrients such as omega-3 fatty acids and antioxidants, in addition to macronutrients that are essential for our bodies to function. However, for survival, a diet that is heavy in macronutrients is necessary, and micronutrients can be ignored for at least the first month. After that, it&#39;s crucial to reintroduce them to maintain good health. So, what are these macronutrients?</p>

							<p>Macronutrients are essential nutrients that our bodies need in large quantities to perform necessary functions. They include carbohydrates, proteins, and fats.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Carbohydrates are the body&#39;s primary source of energy, and we can obtain them from foods such as bread, rice, and fruits.&nbsp;</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Proteins help build and repair tissues, and we can find them in foods such as meat, eggs, and beans.&nbsp;</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Fats provide the body with energy, help with the absorption of vitamins, and are found in foods such as nuts, butter, and oils.</li>
							</ul>

							<p>When preparing a survival stockpile, it is important to choose non-perishable food items that do not require refrigeration. This is because power outages are a common occurrence during disasters, making it difficult to keep perishable foods fresh. While it may be tempting to stock up on favorite foods, this is not always practical. Fresh and frozen foods are not suitable for long-term storage without refrigeration, and many junk foods do not provide efficient nutrients.</p>

							<p>Therefore, when creating a survival stockpile, it is best to focus on non-perishable food items that provide essential macronutrients, such as carbohydrates, fats, and proteins. This ensures that you have a supply of food that will provide the necessary energy and building blocks for your body to function properly during a crisis. By choosing foods that do not require refrigeration, you can avoid the risk of spoilage and waste, and ensure that your family has access to healthy, nourishing meals during a disaster.</p>

							<p>Instead of stockpiling fresh or frozen foods, it&#39;s best to choose non-perishable items for survival. The following items are great options to stockpile:</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Whole grains for baking</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">White rice</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Dry beans for protein</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Pasta, which can expand any meal</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Spaghetti sauce to flavor dishes</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Canned vegetables and fruits</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Dry fruits</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Nuts and peanut butter for protein</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Jelly to pair with peanut butter</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Baking supplies like baking powder and soda</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Cooking oil</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Powdered milk and eggs for baking</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Dehydrated meat and canned meat</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Bouillon for soup stock</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Spices to add flavor to unusual foods</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Sugar and honey for sweetness</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Coffee for a caffeine boost</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Vitamins for micronutrients</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">TVP (textured vegetable protein) as meat substitutes</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Cheese that has been triple-dipped in wax to preserve it</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Powdered drink concentrates</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Granola and granola bars for quick energy</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Purified water, as it&#39;s important to have plenty of it available.</li>
							</ul>

							<p>To determine how much food you need for your stockpile, it is recommended to create a two-week menu, listing all the items you will need, including ingredients for bread or other baked goods. Combine the lists, tallying up the quantities needed for each item, and multiply that by the number of weeks you want to prepare for to determine how much food to buy.</p>

							<p>When considering how long you want your stockpile to last, it&#39;s important to plan for the worst-case scenario, including the recovery time. For instance, a hurricane may only disrupt your city for a few days, but pandemics like COVID-19 have demonstrated that supply chains can take weeks or even months to recover. Therefore, having enough food to sustain you through the disaster and its aftermath is a good starting point.</p>

							<p>After reaching your initial goal, you may want to continue building your stockpile gradually, aiming for a year&#39;s worth of food. However, this will take time to achieve.</p>

							<p><strong>Long-Term Storage of Food</strong></p>

							<p>Repurposing grocery store food for long-term storage is not as straightforward as one may think. While canned goods are usually packaged for extended shelf-life, dry foods often require repackaging to last longer. Fortunately, there is a method to package them, allowing them to stay edible for 20 years or more.</p>

							<p>Expiration dates on canned goods in metal cans or glass jars can be ignored. These dates do not indicate food spoilage but rather the date until which the canner guarantees that the food retains its nutritional value. The only legal requirement for an expiration date is for baby formula. Canned goods that are decades old have been opened and found to be perfectly safe to consume. However, canned goods in plastic containers may not last as gases can seep through the plastic.</p>

							<p>For long-term storage of dry goods, aluminized Mylar bags with oxygen absorbers should be used and stored inside five-gallon plastic buckets. This ensures protection from all types of pests and guarantees the food will still be edible when opened. Online retailers sell Mylar bags and oxygen absorbers, while food-grade buckets are available at local home improvement centers.</p>

							<p>To pack food this way:</p>

							<ol>
								<li style="list-style-type:decimal">Gather a large amount of food as oxygen absorbers work quickly and it&#39;s best to do a lot at once.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:decimal">Open six-gallon aluminized Mylar bags and place them inside five-gallon buckets.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:decimal">Fill the bags with food, leaving about an inch below the bucket&#39;s rim. It&#39;s recommended to remove the original packaging and put only one type of food in each bucket.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:decimal">Label the contents of the bucket in several places on the outside.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:decimal">Use a hair straightener to seal the top two inches of the bag, leaving a two-inch gap at one end.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:decimal">Quickly insert an oxygen absorber into the bag&#39;s opening. Having an assistant to seal the package of oxygen absorbers back up may be helpful.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:decimal">Quickly place the vacuum cleaner hose just inside the opening of the bag&#39;s seal and remove as much air as possible. Avoid putting the hose or nozzle too far inside, or food will be sucked out.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:decimal">Remove the vacuum cleaner hose and seal the bag completely.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:decimal">Fold over the bag&#39;s ends to lay flat on top of the food, then hammer the lid onto the bucket with a rubber mallet.</li>
							</ol>

							<p>It&#39;s important to store food stored using this method in a cool and dry area. The buckets are waterproof, except for the wire handle, allowing for the possibility of creating hidden caches of food by burying them. When storing food in your home, it&#39;s recommended to scatter it into different, preferably hidden locations. This is to ensure that in case someone breaks into your home looking for food, they won&#39;t be able to find all of it.</p>

							<p><br />
							&nbsp;</p>

							<p><strong>Managing Your Supplies</strong></p>

							<p>To ensure that you are not wasting your food stockpile, portion control is essential, even if it means leaving family members hungry. Your survival menu should not only consider the nutrients in the food but also total calories. Therefore, it is recommended to develop 2,000, 1,800, and 1,500 calorie per day plans. In severe situations, you may have to cut down on food consumption to make it last longer. Although living on 1,500 calories per day may cause you to lose weight, it is still possible to survive.</p>

							<p>It is important to remember that those who have not prepared will not have the same resources as you and your family. They may be losing weight and struggling to find food. By contrast, if your family is not losing weight, it could be seen as an indication that you have plenty of food to eat. Although a low-calorie diet may not be enjoyable, it is ultimately better for your family&#39;s safety than being attacked by hungry individuals who want to steal your food and are willing to harm you to get it.</p>

							<p>In conclusion, rationing your supplies and controlling portion sizes will be essential to make your food last longer in emergency situations. Developing menus with different calorie options can also be beneficial in conserving your food resources. Finally, remember that being well-prepared may give you an advantage over others who are not, and taking precautions to avoid being a target for those who are desperate for food is crucial for your family&#39;s safety.</p>

							<p><strong>Cooking in the Absence of Power or Gas Supply</strong></p>

							<p>It is highly likely that electricity will be unavailable during any disaster, with power outages being caused by even a strong storm. Our electrical grid is a fragile part of the infrastructure, and anything more severe than a storm will likely result in power outages. In addition, natural gas companies may stop pumping gas if the situation is dire enough. But how can you cook without electricity or gas? The solution is not as daunting as it seems, as people have been cooking for centuries without modern stoves. There are several options to consider:</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Coleman &quot;dual fuel&quot; stove - burns gasoline</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Barbecue grille - can burn wood, regardless of propane or charcoal type, always have an extra tank for propane</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Fire pit - can be modified with grates for cooking, typically burns wood</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Fireplace or wood-burning stove - centuries-old option for cooking in homes, some newer models may be harder to use for cooking.</li>
							</ul>

							<p>Consider adding a solar oven to your arsenal of cooking methods. A simple solar oven typically consists of a box with clear plastic or glass on the front and reflective panels on the sides that direct sunlight into the box. The heat generated by the sunlight cooks the food inside the box. Cooking with a solar oven is similar to using a slow cooker, so it&#39;s important to allow plenty of time for the food to cook.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>OTHER ESSENTIAL ITEMS TO STOCKPILE</strong></p>

							<p>A prepping stockpile typically consists of food and water, but it&#39;s important to remember that we use other items on a daily or nearly daily basis as well. That&#39;s why we need to stockpile everything that meets our survival necessities. While it may be impossible to stockpile everything we need, every item we add to our stockpile is one more that will make life easier in a post-disaster world.</p>

							<p>However, it&#39;s important to note that we&#39;re talking about survival necessities here - the things that meet our critical needs. Each family is unique, so it&#39;s important to take their needs into consideration when building a stockpile. Additionally, it&#39;s worth considering things that will help your family survive the isolation of survival, without having access to their usual entertainment options like cell phones, video games, or the internet.</p>

							<p>While we won&#39;t list any specific items, it&#39;s important to think about what your family needs and what will make their lives easier during a disaster. We should all have a good idea of what these things are, considering the COVID-19 pandemic and the stay-at-home orders that many people experienced. Ultimately, the goal is to stockpile items that will help us survive and thrive during and after a disaster.</p>

							<p><strong>Heating and Lighting Options For Emergency Situations</strong></p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Stockpile <strong>firewood</strong> for heating your home with a fireplace or wood-burning stove</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Have a couple of good, windproof <strong>butane lighters</strong> with fuel for refilling</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Have alternative <strong>fire starters</strong> and accelerants for damp wood</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Each family member should have their own <strong>flashlight</strong>, and have extra mounted in clips in each room</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Stock up on <strong>AA and AAA batteries</strong> for flashlights and portable electronics</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Consider using <strong>oil lamps</strong> or candles as an alternative source of lighting</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Stock up on <strong>candle wicks</strong> to make additional <strong>candles</strong> or melt down used ones.</li>
							</ul>

							<p><strong>Food and Water for Emergency Situations</strong></p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Water filter cartridges</strong> &ndash; If you have a cartridge-type water filter, you&#39;ll need plenty of filter cartridges.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Bleach</strong> &ndash; You can use bleach for cleaning, sanitizing, and purifying water, and it&#39;s cheap.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Heirloom seeds, Fertilizers, and garden chemicals</strong> &ndash; For growing your own food.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Vitamins &ndash; To supplement your diet and get all the necessary nutrients, especially micronutrients.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Pet food and Baby formula</strong> &ndash; If you have pets or a baby.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>First-aid supplies</strong> &ndash; A large first-aid kit focusing on major trauma.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Over-the-counter medicine</strong>s &ndash; Including antihistamines, decongestants, cough suppressants, hydrocortisone cream, pain relievers, and loperamide or Imodium for diarrhea.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Antibiotics and Prescription medicines</strong> &ndash; For chronic conditions or purchased from Mexico or veterinary versions.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Pesticides</strong> &ndash; To keep mice, rats, and cockroaches out of your home.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Personal hygiene supplies and Feminine hygiene supplies</strong> &ndash; To maintain personal hygiene and comfort.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Toilet paper, Soap, Hand sanitizer, and Cleaning supplies</strong> &ndash; To keep yourself and your home clean to avoid disease.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Hazmat personal protection equipment</strong> &ndash; For leaving your home in the midst of an epidemic.</li>
							</ul>

							<p><strong>Maintenance</strong></p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Home repair materials </strong>&ndash; In the event of natural disasters, your home may become damaged. Keep materials for emergency repairs to protect yourself from scalpers.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Hardware</strong> &ndash; Stock up on hardware for general repairs and to go with your home repair materials.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Hand tools</strong> &ndash; Power tools won&#39;t work during power outages. Keep a set of hand tools as a backup.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Coleman mantles &amp; pump repair kits</strong> &ndash; Have repair kits on hand for your Coleman lanterns and stoves in case they break down.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Other repair parts</strong> &ndash; Stock up on repair parts for any critical survival gear you have.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Sewing supplies</strong> &ndash; Keep sewing supplies to repair or alter clothing in case of weight loss.</li>
							</ul>

							<p><strong>Others</strong></p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Survival clothing &ndash; Rugged clothing suitable for harsh weather and physical work</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Ammunition &ndash; Stock up on ammunition for all the firearms you own</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Sandbags &ndash; If you live in flood or hurricane-prone areas, you might need sandbags to protect your home</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Plastic bags &ndash; Get a variety of sizes to use for various purposes</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Fuel &ndash; Have a good supply of gasoline for your car, lawnmower, and chain saw. Oil lamps may also come in handy</li>
							</ul>

							<p>When it comes to prepping for emergencies, there is no one-size-fits-all solution. It is important to consider your own situation, especially the things you use regularly. With the assumption that stores won&#39;t have what you need during an emergency, it&#39;s a good idea to have some spares.</p>

							<p>One way to stock up on emergency supplies is to buy extra when you are already purchasing them. This is more budget-friendly and saves time. For instance, if you typically buy a big pack of paper towels, you could increase your stocking level to two packs, then later to three. This way, stockpiling becomes a natural part of your routine, rather than a chore.</p>

							<p>Moreover, buying items on sale can help save money and build up your prepping stockpile. Many common items go on sale annually or quarterly, and there&#39;s nothing wrong with buying enough for the entire year when they are on sale. The author has been working this way for years, only buying items on sale, from laundry detergent to computer paper, keeping their stockpile up while saving money.</p>

							<p>In conclusion, while this is not an exhaustive list, it is a starting point to consider for emergency preparedness. It is vital to assess your own needs and consider what you use on a daily basis to make sure you have the necessary items in case of an emergency. By increasing your normal stocking levels and taking advantage of sales, you can save money and build up your stockpile at the same time.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>PROTECTING YOURSELF DURING A PANDEMIC</strong></p>

							<p>In the previous chapter, I included HAZMAT personal protection equipment as an important item to stockpile. We&#39;ve all witnessed how medical masks, gloves, and hand sanitizers became scarce almost overnight during the pandemic. I monitored stores daily to observe how the impending pandemic was affecting inventory levels and saw how items were quickly snatched off the shelves from one day to the next. If another pandemic occurs (which is highly possible), we can expect a similar scenario to unfold.</p>

							<p>The COVID-19 pandemic has demonstrated the devastating effects pandemics can have in the modern world. Air travel has enabled pathogens such as SARS-CoV-2 to spread around the world in a matter of days. With diseases like this having lengthy incubation periods, they can infect thousands of people before anyone even realizes it&#39;s there.</p>

							<p>The issue lies partly in the consumption of unusual food in China and other regions of the world. Whether the virus originated from the meat market or the bio-research lab in China, it came from a bat like many other diseases. The virus does not harm its host animal but can be catastrophic when it infects humans. It is possible for another epidemic or pandemic to spread across the world again and cause widespread death. In comparison, the Coronavirus pandemic was relatively mild in terms of fatalities. Imagine the devastation if a disease like Ebola were to spread in a similar manner.</p>

							<p>While I&#39;m withholding judgment on whether the government&#39;s actions destroyed the economy until I see how quickly it rebounds, I believe that many of the measures taken were appropriate in slowing down the spread of the disease. These measures include telecommuting for those who can, closing schools, public events, and other meeting places, social distancing to avoid coughs and sneezes, washing hands thoroughly, and wearing multi-layered cloth masks (not medical masks) to prevent the disease from spreading. Avoiding unnecessary trips to crowded public areas is also important.</p>

							<p>Initially, when the novel coronavirus was announced, people in certain countries, such as Japan, took the initiative to wear masks without being told, which helped in slowing the spread of the disease. Japan also became the first country to shut down its schools, further reducing the spread of the virus. While there has been some debate over the efficacy of masks, statistics show that they can be highly effective:</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">If healthy people wear masks but infected individuals don&#39;t, there is a 70% chance of contracting the disease.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">If infected individuals wear masks but healthy people don&#39;t, there is only a 5% chance of catching the disease.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">If both infected and healthy individuals wear masks, the likelihood of catching the disease drops to only 1.5%.</li>
							</ul>

							<p>It is clear that wearing masks is the best defense against pandemics. Therefore, if there is news about a potential outbreak, it is wise to start wearing masks immediately, even if there are no known cases in your area. Personally, I would rather be considered overly cautious for wearing a mask than risk catching a deadly disease by leaving it off to avoid appearing strange.</p>

							<p>This also means preparing a stockpile of essential supplies to fight against a pandemic, such as:</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Cloth masks, N-95 masks, or chemical respirators, which are better than surgical masks.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Disposable gloves, for use only in places like the supermarket, and discarded after leaving.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Tyvek booties to wear over shoes in supermarkets to prevent carrying the SARS-CoV-2 virus into homes.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Hand sanitizer for situations where there is no water.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Disinfectants and disinfectant wipes for cleaning everything, especially items brought into the home.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Vitamins to boost the immune system.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Tyvek suits for use as HAZMAT suits if you need to go to a highly infected area.</li>
							</ul>

							<p><strong>Disinfection</strong></p>

							<p>To ensure that your home is free of contamination, it is crucial to assume that everything you bring in is contaminated unless proven otherwise. Therefore, it is recommended to set up a decontamination station at your doorstep and use disinfectants like chlorine bleach, 60% or greater alcohol, or 3% hydrogen peroxide to clean every package before bringing it inside. For difficult-to-clean packaging, open it and remove the contents, which can be cleaned, and dispose of the packaging in an outdoor trash can.</p>

							<p>However, certain items like fruits and vegetables should not be decontaminated with these chemicals. Instead, they should be washed with normal soap and water in the sink to remove bacteria and kill viruses, just like washing your hands. By taking these precautions, you can ensure that your home remains a safe and healthy environment.</p>

							<p><strong>DIY Sanitizer</strong></p>

							<p>Amidst the COVID-19 outbreak, hand sanitizer quickly became scarce in stores, leading many people to create their own. However, due to a lack of knowledge or carelessness, numerous individuals made the sanitizer incorrectly, resulting in a product with inadequate disinfectant properties. Although the CDC recommends a minimum of 60% alcohol content for effective sanitation, many individuals utilized 70% alcohol in their homemade recipes but failed to account for the addition of other ingredients, ultimately leaving them with a final alcohol content of only 45%. To ensure the correct composition, one should use the following recipe: 2 cups (1 pint) of 91% rubbing alcohol, 1 cup of aloe vera gel, and 15 drops of antibacterial essential oil, such as tea tree or lavender oil.</p>

							<p><strong>Disinfecting with Clorox Wipes and Other Disinfectants during Pandemics</strong></p>

							<p>When it comes to disinfecting products, Clorox is a household name and a popular choice for many. Its effectiveness as a disinfectant can be attributed to the powerful properties of bleach, which is known for its ability to sanitize and is often used for cleaning in commercial kitchens. The Clorox disinfectant and cleaner is available in a convenient spray bottle or as Clorox wipes, a popular choice for quick and easy sanitization.</p>

							<p>If you run out of Clorox disinfectant or wipes, you can easily make your own at home using simple ingredients.</p>

							<p>To create the cleaner and disinfectant, mix 1/3 cup of plain Clorox bleach (not scented or color-safe) with one gallon of water and 1/2 cup of dishwashing liquid.</p>

							<p>To make your own Clorox wipes, follow the above recipe and then cut a roll of blue paper towels sold in auto parts stores in half, making them roughly the same size as a roll of toilet paper. Soak the roll of towels in the disinfectant until they are fully saturated, then remove the cardboard core. Place the roll into a container, such as an empty wipes container or a large square container. Pull out the end of the towel from the center of the roll and start using. To keep the towels wet, pour about 1/4 cup of the disinfectant into the bottom of the container.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>HOW TO START A FIRE</strong></p>

							<p>Starting a fire is a fundamental skill that is crucial for survival in any outdoor or emergency situation. Despite its importance, many people struggle with starting a fire. It may seem like a simple task, but it requires a basic understanding of fire-building techniques and materials.</p>

							<p>In many cases, people who struggle with starting a fire simply do not know how to do it correctly. They may attempt to light a fire with insufficient materials or use ineffective techniques that fail to ignite the flames. These individuals may find themselves in serious trouble if they ever need to start a fire to survive.</p>

							<p><strong>How</strong></p>

							<p>Fire starting can be easy if you know what materials to use. These materials can be categorized into three basic groups: tinder, kindling, and fuel. Tinder refers to small pieces of material that catch fire easily, such as dry grass, char-cloth, cotton balls, cattail fluff, dry leaves, dry bark, or dandelion clock. Kindling consists of small sticks, approximately the diameter of your finger, that can ignite from the tinder. This can include split pieces of &ldquo;fuzz sticks&rdquo;. Fuel refers to split pieces of dry tree branch or trunk, about the diameter of your arm, that can ignite from the kindling. It is important that the heartwood is exposed, as bark will protect the wood from burning.</p>

							<p>When laying the fire, it is crucial to lay it in a way that ignites the tinder first. Once the tinder catches fire, it will ignite the kindling, which can then ignite the fuel. The most common way to accomplish this is by making a teepee or a stepped pyramid out of the materials.</p>

							<p>Recently, some people have suggested using a top-down fire starting method, where the kindling is piled on top of the fuel, with the tinder on top of that. However, this method doesn&#39;t always work because heat rises, it doesn&rsquo;t go down.</p>

							<p>Once the fire is burning well, you can add full logs to it. Many people will lay a large log or two in their fire at night, so that it has enough to burn through until morning.</p>

							<p><strong>Starters</strong></p>

							<p>Fire starters can be divided into two main categories: primary and secondary. The only fire starters that are considered primary are matches and lighters, as they are the most effective. Everything else, including Ferro Rods, are considered to be secondary fire starters. It is recommended to have a couple of secondary fire starters on hand in case something happens to your primary ones, although primary fire starters should be used whenever possible to save effort.</p>

							<p>One of the biggest issues with most fire starters is that they are often ineffective in windy or rainy conditions. Waterproof matches are commonly recommended as a primary fire starter, particularly those that are strike anywhere matches. However, even waterproof matches can be ineffective in windy conditions. Storm proof matches are a good investment, as they can be ignited and burned in the wind or rain, and even underwater. Similarly, storm proof lighters, such as electric arc or piezoelectric fired butane gas lighters, are constantly igniting, preventing them from going out in adverse weather conditions.</p>

							<p>The Ferro Rod is the most common secondary fire starter, but it can be challenging to use as it only produces a few sparks, especially with smaller ones. Some larger Ferro Rods are made of magnesium, which is more effective despite being mistakenly referred to as Ferro Rods. The Blastmatch or Sparkie are good alternatives to Ferro Rods, as they are magnesium rods mounted into a spring-loaded handle, with a striker that produces many more sparks, increasing the likelihood of starting a fire.</p>

							<p>For a simpler and cheaper secondary fire starter, a Metal Match is an option. It consists of a block of magnesium with a Ferro Rod embedded into one edge. Some magnesium dust is scraped off with a knife, and the Ferro Rod is used to create a spark, igniting the magnesium, which burns at a high temperature, making it very effective.</p>

							<p><strong>Starting a Fire in Wet Weather Conditions</strong></p>

							<p>Starting a fire in wet weather can be a challenging task, even for the best of fire starters. One of the biggest problems is finding dry tinder, kindling, and fuel. In the past, our ancestors would carry a tinder box with them to keep their tinder dry and a flint and steel to start a fire. While dry tinder is a good starting point, you need dry kindling and fuel as well. One way to find dry kindling and fuel is to look in sheltered places where the rain cannot reach it. Fallen trees, caves or overhangs, and thickets are some examples of sheltered areas.</p>

							<p>It is also important to have a protected area where you can lay your fire. A rock bed can be useful as it will keep the fire off of the wet ground. Adding a windbreak such as stones, piled wood, a tarp, or a rescue blanket on the upwind side of the fire can help protect it from the wind and rain. Overhead protection in the form of tree branches can also prevent the rain from extinguishing the fire.</p>

							<p>It&#39;s essential to gather dry wood, but it&#39;s okay to gather damp wood as well. Just remember that the damp wood will need to be placed near the fire for some time to dry out. You can use the damp wood as part of the windbreak or a heat reflector, and it will dry out while helping you get the most out of your fire.</p>

							<p><strong>Enhancers</strong></p>

							<p>Starting a fire in wet weather can be a challenge, even with the best preparation and ingredients. In such situations, it may be necessary to use a chemical accelerant to get the fire going. Accelerants are any flammable chemicals used to start a fire, and while the term is typically associated with arson, it is also applicable in this case.</p>

							<p>There are chemical accelerants specifically designed for survival purposes that can be purchased. They are often marketed as &quot;fire starters,&quot; although this can be confusing as it refers to the fire starters mentioned earlier. The WetFire cube is one of the most effective chemical accelerants, and even a small piece of it can start a fire in the harshest of conditions.</p>

							<p>Alternatively, an excellent fire accelerant can be made using cotton balls and petroleum jelly. To create this, place a cotton ball into a bowl and use the back of a spoon to scoop out about a teaspoon of petroleum jelly. Work the petroleum jelly into the cotton ball until it is evenly distributed. These cotton balls can then be ignited using any of the fire starters mentioned above and will burn for over three minutes at a high enough temperature to dry out and ignite damp kindling.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>PART 2 - DEVELOPING A RELIABLE STRATEGY</strong></p>

							<p>When it comes to surviving a crisis or disaster, it&#39;s often more practical to use your home as a shelter rather than abandoning it for an uncertain future. Staying at home means having access to all of your possessions, and even non-survival items can prove useful in certain circumstances. However, in order to survive at home, there are important steps and decisions you need to make to be prepared.</p>

							<p>In the first section, we talked about quick actions you can take to increase your family&#39;s chances of survival, such as stockpiling food and water. But that&#39;s just the beginning. In this section, we&#39;ll go deeper and create a comprehensive survival plan. Some of the things we&#39;ll discuss may take longer to implement, but they will greatly increase your chances of survival and prepare you for a longer period of time.</p>

							<p>It&#39;s important to remember that every step you take towards preparedness will make a difference in your family&#39;s survival. Even small efforts can have a big impact. So, we&#39;ll cover a range of topics in this section, including building your stockpile, creating a communication plan, fortifying your home, and much more. By the end, you&#39;ll have a solid plan in place to ensure your family&#39;s safety and well-being in the event of a disaster or crisis.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>BE MENTALLY REPARED</strong></p>

							<p>Survival involves more than just physical preparation; it also requires the right mental attitude. In fact, military manuals on survival always start with a section discussing the development of a &ldquo;survival mentality.&rdquo; This attitude is characterized by the belief that you can survive, regardless of the circumstances. It has been proven effective in a wide range of survival situations, including those that are not related to the outdoors.</p>

							<p>Studies have shown that police officers who are shot in the line of duty are more likely to survive if they believe they will survive, and cancer patients with a positive attitude are more likely to survive than those who believe that cancer will kill them. This is due to the will to live, which drives people to do whatever is necessary to survive. Those who lack this will are more likely to give up and let fate have its way.</p>

							<p>The will to live is crucial in survival situations, as it motivates us through the hard physical work required to survive. We must be convinced that we can do it, and training is key to building that confidence. As we learn more survival skills and prepare ourselves by buying the right gear and supplies, we become more confident in our ability to survive. This is evident in the military, where training gives soldiers the confidence they need to survive. The more training they have, the more confident they become, and highly trained groups like Delta Force or the Navy SEALs are made up of highly confident people.</p>

							<p>In summary, developing a survival mentality is crucial to survival. It requires the belief that you can survive and the will to live, which motivates us through the hard physical work required to survive. With training and preparation, we can build the confidence we need to survive in any situation.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>PROTECT YOUR PRIVACY AND INFORMATION</strong></p>

							<p>In the world of survival preparation, the concept of operational security, also known as OPSEC, is highly valued. This military term holds great significance for us as we prepare for the next disaster. It is essential to understand that we are vastly outnumbered by individuals who do not possess the skills or willingness to survive. Some may rely on the government for assistance while others may scoff at the idea of preparing for disaster altogether. However, the most perilous group are those who may come knocking at our doors, expecting us to care for them. Therefore, it is crucial to take necessary precautions to protect ourselves and maintain operational security.</p>

							<p>The concept of operational security, or &quot;OPSEC,&quot; is crucial for those preparing for the next disaster. Unfortunately, many people are unwilling to prepare for such events, putting those who do at risk. It&#39;s not uncommon for people to say they&#39;ll just come knocking on your door if something happens. While charity is important, it&#39;s impossible to stockpile enough resources for everyone. It&#39;s best to focus on helping those closest to you with a limited amount of supplies.</p>

							<p>Allowing strangers to come to your door for assistance can be dangerous, as they may resort to violence if refused. The best approach is to maintain secrecy about your preparations to prevent people from knowing what you have. The more people know about your supplies, the more likely they are to come knocking. To maintain OPSEC, it&#39;s important to limit who you tell and avoid flaunting your preparations.</p>

							<p>How?<br />
							Purchase in secret: Avoid having large shipments show up at your door, unload in a closed garage or backyard</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Hide your stockpile: Conceal your stockpile from friends and family visiting your home; use camouflage if you can&#39;t hide it</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Disinformation: Mislead neighbors by saying your alternative energy source (e.g., wind turbine or solar panels) is not for emergency power but for alternative energy</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Avoid looking like an armed camp: Don&#39;t do things that make your home look like a concentration camp (e.g., building a 10-foot high cement wall)</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Don&#39;t look &quot;tacticool&quot;: Avoid clothing or accessories that make you look like a prepper or survivalist</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Keep it from your kids: Kids can&#39;t keep secrets, so avoid telling them about your preparations</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">During a disaster: Avoid having trash piled up, find ways to cook without giving away the scent of food, practice noise and light discipline (keep the volume down and use blackout curtains)</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Practice noise discipline: Keep the volume down on your electrical devices (music, movies) so that the neighbors cannot hear it.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Practice light discipline: Cover your windows with blackout curtains to prevent light from escaping.</li>
							</ul>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>Group Survival VS. Solo Survival: Which is Better?</strong></p>

							<p>It&#39;s not uncommon for people to develop a lone-wolf survival mentality, thinking that they can survive on their own without help from others. This is especially true if others view them as a &quot;survival expert.&quot; However, this mindset can be dangerous and misguided.</p>

							<p>The idea of the lone-wolf survivalist can be romanticized, with images of mountain men surviving on their own in the past. However, those men were often much tougher and more rugged than modern individuals. Many still died from various hazards, including animal attacks, accidents, and hypothermia.</p>

							<p>The world that the mountain men lived in was different from today&#39;s world. Nature provided much of what they needed, and they didn&#39;t have to worry about contaminated water sources. Today, we have to face not only the risks of nature but also two-legged predators who may harm us during a crisis.</p>

							<p>Although mountain men did face problems with American Indians, the sparse population of Native Americans meant that meeting them was unlikely. When they did interact, they were not usually intent on murder, contrary to what history books may suggest. In fact, some mountain men had good relations with various Indian tribes.</p>

							<p>However, the risks faced by modern individuals during a crisis are much higher, with hungry mobs willing to steal food and kill whoever stands in their way. Trying to survive as a lone-wolf is too risky unless someone is confident that they can take on a gang of 10 or 12 adversaries.</p>

							<p>Going it alone in a survival situation can be incredibly challenging due to the sheer amount of work that needs to be done. From defense to gathering and purifying water, growing food, making repairs, and everything in between, the workload can quickly become overwhelming, especially in a long-term scenario. Having a survival team can help to alleviate this burden by spreading the workload and sharing the responsibility of defense. Additionally, there is safety in numbers, as attackers are less likely to target a group than an individual or a small family.</p>

							<p>However, finding like-minded individuals to form a survival group with can be a challenge. Many survivalists are secretive about their activities, as discussed in the previous chapter. But there are places where you can find them, such as shooting ranges. It may take some effort and patience to locate and connect with potential group members, but it can be done.</p>

							<p>Forming a survival group also offers the opportunity to bring together individuals with different areas of expertise. This allows for a more efficient division of labor, as each member can focus on their areas of strength while still receiving cross-training in other essential skills. While there should be some overlap in knowledge and abilities within the group, having specialists in different areas can help to ensure that all necessary tasks are covered.</p>

							<p>So, what types of skills should you prioritize when forming a survival group?</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">General survival: It&#39;s important to have at least one member of the group who is a true survival expert.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Military (especially infantry): You will need to defend yourselves.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Medical: A team medic is necessary to take care of injuries.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Gardening or farming: You will need someone who can grow food for the team.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Animal husbandry: Raising animals for food is another important skill to have.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Food preservation: You need someone who can preserve the food you grow.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">General repairs: Someone who can fix things and keep everything working is essential.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Some additional skills you might want to have:</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Midwifery: Someone who can help women during childbirth.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Hunting: Raising animals is more efficient, but hunting for food is still useful.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Fishing: Another way to bring in food.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Communications: A ham radio operator can help you keep in touch with the world and find out what&#39;s going on.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Blacksmith: If you can find one, they can make just about anything out of metal, including tools and weapons.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Woodworking: Someone who can make things you might need.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Tanning &amp; leatherworking: Someone who can turn animal hides into leather and that leather into useful things.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Cobbler: A lost art these days, but someone who can repair shoes is useful.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Teacher: Someone who can teach the children.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Sewing and/or weaving: Making cloth and turning that cloth into clothing. Altering clothing that you find.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Counselor: A minister or professional counselor might be needed to help people adjust to the situation.</li>
							</ul>

							<p>It&#39;s important to clarify that being an expert in a certain area doesn&#39;t mean that person will do everything in that area. Rather, they will lead in that area and everyone will contribute as they can. It&#39;s not fair for someone to be idle just because they&#39;re the &quot;communicator&quot; and expect others to provide for them.</p>

							<p>While having the right skills is important, it&#39;s even more important to have people who can get along with each other. Strife within the group can lead to implosion and leave everyone in a bad situation.</p>

							<p>A leader will need to be chosen, and it&#39;s up to the group how they select that person. They should prioritize the needs of the group and be fair in their dealings with everyone. Ideally, the leader should be someone who doesn&#39;t want the job, as this can indicate they&#39;re not in it for power. They should also possess good leadership skills and be respected by the group.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>SURVIVAL IN URBAN VS. RURAL ENVIRONMENTS</strong></p>

							<p>In the United States, the majority of the population, approximately 80%, lives in urban areas. This figure can be further broken down as 52% living in suburban areas and 28% living in urban areas, also known as &quot;center city.&quot; Only 20% of the overall population lives in rural areas.</p>

							<p>Many people believe that those living in rural areas have an advantage in survival situations due to a lower population density to availability of resources ratio. While this is generally true, there is a common misconception that rural areas, especially farming communities, have an abundance of food that can be shared with people living in urban areas. In reality, unless it is just after harvest time, farming communities typically only have enough food for their own needs, rather than enough to feed the world.</p>

							<p>When it comes to prepping and surviving a disaster, most of the information available is written from the viewpoint of suburbia. Many preppers believe that it makes more sense to live in a suburban area or on the edge of a suburban area, where they have enough land for gardening and even raising chickens.</p>

							<p>There are several specific differences between urban and rural survival. Let&rsquo;s discuss each.</p>

							<p><strong>Government Assistance</strong></p>

							<p>When it comes to aid during a disaster, preppers are not big fans of government aid, as they believe that FEMA doesn&rsquo;t have a good reputation for providing aid effectively. Even if they do provide aid, it&#39;s usually in the form of financial aid, which comes with many restrictions and may cause more problems for people in the long run. However, it&#39;s worth noting that if there is any government aid to be had, it will be directed towards big cities first, and it may not make it much farther than that. While we shouldn&#39;t rely solely on government aid, it&#39;s likely that people will be grateful for whatever assistance they can get when the time comes.</p>

							<p>In addition to aid, law and order will also be associated with any government action taken during a disaster. While crime rates are typically higher in large cities, the police presence is generally more significant as well. This larger police presence can be helpful in combating the gangs that tend to emerge in the aftermath of a major disaster. However, it&#39;s important to note that this assumes that the police organization remains intact during the disaster. If the police organization breaks down, it could make the situation even more dangerous.</p>

							<p><strong>Food and Water Supply</strong></p>

							<p>Living in an urban center presents a unique challenge for preppers. Due to the lack of space, it is difficult for city-dwellers to stockpile large amounts of food and water. Additionally, access to groundwater or the ability to grow their own food is limited for most urban residents. Those living in rural areas or on the outskirts of suburban areas have an advantage in this regard as they typically have larger lots and the ability to grow their own food.</p>

							<p>Living in rural areas or the outskirts of suburbs provides preppers with the ability to become self-sufficient rather than just relying on stockpiling. With larger lots, they have the space to grow vegetables, fruit trees, and raise animals for food. They can also drill wells for water or use rainwater capture. This allows them to change their survival focus from solely stockpiling to becoming self-sufficient.</p>

							<p>The suburbs provide a good balance between urban and rural areas. However, the closer one gets to the city center, the more they have to depend on stockpiling and the less they can rely on growing their own food. Those living in the city center will face the need to evacuate sooner than those in rural areas in the event of a TEOTWAWKI event. In such scenarios, unprepared people will likely move towards rural areas in search of essential supplies.</p>

							<p>The migration of people can be advantageous to preppers living in the city center, as they will have enough supplies to see them through. Once the city empties out, they will have access to a significant amount of non-food resources that they can scavenge. They could potentially be the group of people with the potential to rebuild society.</p>

							<p><strong>Personal Protection/Self Defense</strong></p>

							<p>Rural communities face a significant disadvantage in terms of self-defense. Although more people in these communities may own guns, they are also spread out over a greater area. This dispersion will make it difficult for them to coordinate a cohesive defense. Their only option may be to blockade the entrances to their towns, but unless they have natural barriers to support them, these blockades will be ineffective against the hordes of people leaving cities in search of vital resources. These individuals will be desperate and prepared to do whatever it takes to get what they need. If they are unable to reach the small towns by road, they will resort to cross-country travel. Since most will be traveling on foot, there will be little stopping them.</p>

							<p>To make matters worse, these desperate people will seek out isolated homes to attack, attempting to steal whatever they can. Many families will be killed as they try to defend their homes alone, overwhelmed by sheer numbers.</p>

							<p>Living in the center city will provide little solace, unless a home or apartment is exceedingly secure. Rather than loosely-formed gangs gathering together merely to steal food, it will be organized gangs that have existed long before the disaster, with many involved in criminal activity. Before moving out into the countryside in search of food, these gangs will attempt to find food within their own neighborhoods. Violent crime in the inner city will surge until these gangs realize they must venture farther afield to find what they need.</p>

							<p>Once again, it is the people in the suburbs who will have the most significant advantage, provided they organize themselves to defend their homes. The proximity of homes, as well as cul-de-sacs, provides an opportunity to create a defensive perimeter and protect their homes. However, this will only be effective if there are enough people in the neighborhood who have firearms and know how to use them.</p>

							

							<p><strong><span style="font-size:15pt"><span style="font-family:Roboto,sans-serif"><span style="color:#343541">A Comparison of a Short-Term and Long-Term Perspectives</strong></p>

							<p>Looking into the future, we can expect significant changes in three areas. Rural areas are likely to have the highest survival rate, thanks to their abundance of food per capita. However, they will have to adjust to a more primitive lifestyle, as they will not have access to electricity or other resources that are necessary for rebuilding society.</p>

							<p>On the other hand, those in the center of the city will have the most access to resources necessary for rebuilding society in the long term, assuming they survive. However, the key will be the lack of basic resources. Those who have stockpiles of food and access to water will be the only ones with any food at all, unless the government is able to bring food into the city. Once again, government efforts will likely focus on the cities and not the rural areas.</p>

							

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>MAINTAINING A WARM HOME</strong></p>

							

							<p>In this section of the book, we will discuss the importance of maintaining body heat as a survival priority, especially in cold weather. However, the topic was not discussed in the previous section, for two reasons. Firstly, depending on the location and time of year of the disaster, heating the home may not be necessary. Secondly, making the necessary changes to the home to enable heating without electricity is not a quick fix and may take some time.</p>

							<p>Most modern homes are heated with electricity, natural gas, or propane, using a central HVAC system. Even if the heat is generated by burning natural gas, electricity is still needed to run the controls and power the blower or pump. In case of a power outage, the heating system will not function. If the outage persists, the natural gas pumping stations may also shut down, leaving homes without any source of heat. Without heating, temperatures inside the house will start dropping within hours and will reach the outside temperature in a day or two, depending on the insulation.</p>

							<p>Surviving for a few days without heating is possible, even in cold climates, but it has its limits. The colder the temperature, the more energy the body needs to keep warm. In a time when food may be scarce, the body will require more energy, putting a strain on the body&#39;s resources.</p>

							<p>The best solution is to have an alternative heating method, such as burning wood. Wood-burning stoves or fireplaces can provide heat and light without electricity. However, using wood as a source of heat requires preparation, such as collecting, chopping, and storing wood, and ensuring proper ventilation. Other alternative heating methods, such as propane heaters or kerosene heaters, may also be considered, but they have their own set of challenges and safety risks. Whatever the heating method chosen, it is crucial to have a plan and the necessary supplies to stay warm in case of a power outage or other emergency.</p>

							<p><strong>Choosing Between Fireplace and Wood-Burning Stove</strong></p>

							<p>Wood is a popular heating choice for many due to its abundance and renewability. For those considering wood as their heating source, the choice usually comes down to a fireplace or a wood-burning stove. While it may seem like an aesthetic decision, there is a significant difference between the two. Fireplaces are inefficient, as they send most of the heat up the chimney. In contrast, wood-burning stoves radiate heat from all sides, making them more effective in heating a room.</p>

							<p>Modern wood-burning stoves have improved designs, complying with EPA regulations to increase burning efficiency. However, it is essential to ensure that the stove you purchase is rated to provide heat. Avoid wood-burning stoves that use wood pellets for fuel, as they require a specific fuel source. Installing any wood-burning stove or fireplace can be challenging, especially if you have a two-story home.</p>

							<p>It is crucial to keep in mind that wood-burning stoves work by radiant heat, making them ineffective in heating the whole house. Heat will rise and may move into upstairs rooms by convection, but the living area will remain the warmest. In cold weather, family members may have to sleep in the living room if their bedrooms are too cold.</p>

							<p><strong>Temporary Wood-Burning Stove Installation</strong></p>

							<p>If you can&#39;t install a wood-burning stove permanently, it may still be possible to use it temporarily in an emergency. To do so, you&#39;ll need to create a fire-resistant area on your floor using clay tiles or bricks. Ensure that you have two layers to prevent sparks from falling through to flammable materials below.</p>

							<p>The chimney can be run out through a window, requiring you to either cut a hole in the glass or remove a pane of glass. If you remove the window pane, you can use a piece of plywood to fill the gap. You&#39;ll also need to purchase elbows to direct the chimney above the stove and outside, ensuring that it reaches above the roof to allow smoke to dissipate.</p>

							<p>While this method may not radiate heat as effectively as older chimney pipe designs, it can still be used with a slight upward slant towards the outside. Once the emergency is over, the stove can be removed and the window can be restored to its normal state.</p>

							<p><strong>Locating Firewood</strong></p>

							<p>To get the best value from your wood-burning stove, it is recommended to use hardwood firewood instead of pine. Hardwoods are known to have a higher energy density, and using four to six cords of hardwood firewood in a winter would provide better value for your money compared to pine.</p>

							<p>One way to acquire firewood is by purchasing it, but it can be quite expensive, with the typical face cord of wood costing between $200 to $500 depending on location. However, there are several ways to acquire firewood for free, such as putting up an announcement in a grocery store or on Craig&#39;s List offering to remove dead trees or limbs for free. You can also check with contractors who need to clear land or the city when trees need to be trimmed.</p>

							<p>Damaged pallets are also a good source of firewood, as they are usually not recycled. You can inquire from places that recycle pallets and ask what they do with the damaged ones. It is essential to store the firewood in a way that protects it from rain, as wet wood can waste a lot of heat energy. Covering it with a tarp is a simple way to prevent the rain from getting to the firewood.</p>

							<p><strong>Others</strong></p>

							<p>Heating your home with wood is the most common method, but it&#39;s not the only option. Propane and kerosene heaters can also be used, but they require a good supply of fuel and are not easily replaceable. Although they may work well in the short-term, they may not be a long-term solution, and wood heating may eventually become necessary. Propane radiant and kerosene heaters don&#39;t need electricity to function, making them a viable option during power outages.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>READY YOUR FIRST AID</strong></p>

							<p>During a disaster, the likelihood of injury increases significantly, especially during physical work such as cutting and hauling wood. This is compounded by the fact that medical facilities become overwhelmed during disasters, as more people are injured by the disaster or its aftermath. Hospital waiting rooms become overcrowded, and patients may face long wait times, even for serious injuries.</p>

							<p>Given this reality, it is essential to be prepared to take care of medical problems yourself, particularly injuries. However, this is not a matter of having a basic first-aid kit. Serious injuries such as cuts from an axe or chainsaw, gunshot wounds, or falls from a roof require a &quot;trauma kit.&quot;</p>

							<p>A trauma kit is more comprehensive than a standard first-aid kit and contains high-quality medical supplies. You can purchase a trauma kit from various sources, or you can create your own. The advantage of making your kit is that you can ensure that it is stocked with quality supplies and spares, allowing you to take care of multiple injuries. Most commercial trauma kits do not provide this option unless you purchase an EMT kit.</p>

							<p>A trauma kit can be housed in anything with compartments, making organization vital to finding what you need quickly. It is essential to prepare a trauma kit before a disaster, so you are not left searching for medical supplies in the midst of an emergency.</p>

							<p><strong>PPE</strong></p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Medical masks</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Goggles or a face shield</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Disposable rubber gloves &ndash; do not have to be medical grade</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Hand sanitizer</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">CPR mask &ndash; for performing mouth-to-mouth resuscitation, without risk of infection</li>
							</ul>

							<p><strong>Medical</strong></p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">For cutting away clothing, have <strong>medical scissors</strong>.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Use ear or forehead types of <strong>thermomete</strong>r as they are the best.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Have a <strong>blood pressure cuff</strong>.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Sharp tweezers</strong> are helpful in removing splinters and foreign matter from wounds.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">To use with the tweezers, have a <strong>jeweler&#39;s eye loupe</strong>.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">In cases where the patient has trouble breathing, use a <strong>nasal parangeal airway</strong>. It is a soft silicone rubber tube that goes down the throat and is inserted through the nose.</li>
							</ul>

							<p><strong>First Aid Kit</strong></p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Syringe or bottle for irrigation - used to clean debris from wounds</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Alcohol wipes - used for disinfection</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Hydrogen peroxide - an alternative disinfectant to alcohol</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">CAT tourniquet - considered the best tourniquet available</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Clotting agent - Celox or QuickClot - used to stop bleeding by promoting clotting</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Israeli bandages - combines a bandage, pressure bandage, and wrap in one</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Antibacterial ointment - used to help prevent infections</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Steri-strips or Butterfly closures - used to close the skin over an open wound, ideal for those who don&#39;t know how to suture</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Gauze rolls or squares - used as basic bandage material to soak up blood. Only the layer touching the skin needs to be sterile.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Cloth adhesive bandages - used for small injuries as they are flexible and durable</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Larger bandages (e.g. sanitary napkins) - used for larger wounds as they are low-cost, sterile, and designed to absorb blood</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Medical tape - both adhesive type and newer &quot;cohesive&quot; tape</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Tagaderm - clear plastic film used to cover skin irritation when medicine needs to be applied.</li>
							</ul>

							<p><strong>Wound on Torso Region</strong></p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">The <strong>chest valve permits air</strong> to exit the chest during exhalation, but closes during inhalation.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">A <strong>needle decompression kit</strong> is utilized when air accumulates in the chest cavity, obstructing the patient&#39;s breathing. This situation commonly occurs following gunshot wounds to the chest, but it is not effective if the lungs are filled with fluid.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Clear plastic kitchen wrap</strong> can serve as an alternative to cohesive medical tape for securing abdominal bandages in emergency situations. It helps to preserve the cleanliness of abdominal wounds while transporting the patient to the hospital.</li>
							</ul>

							<p><strong>Bone and Ligament Damage</strong></p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">A<strong> Sam splint</strong> is a flexible aluminum strip coated with foam rubber on one side, which can be shaped to create a splint for any type of injury.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Elastic bandages</strong> can be used to secure the Sam splint or for sprains. It&#39;s recommended to have a range of widths available.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc"><strong>Instant cold pack</strong>s can help to prevent swelling in case of an injury.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">A c<strong>ombat cravat</strong> is a large triangular bandana that can serve as a sturdy sling for immobilizing an arm or shoulder.</li>
							</ul>

							

							<p><strong>Medication</strong></p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Antibiotics are medications used to treat bacterial infections.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Pain relievers are drugs that alleviate pain, such as headaches or muscle pain.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Antihistamines are used to relieve allergy symptoms, such as sneezing and itching.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Decongestants help to relieve nasal congestion caused by colds or allergies.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Loperamide is a medication used to treat diarrhea.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Lidocaine is a topical anesthetic cream that temporarily numbs the skin.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Benzoine is a liquid solution used to promote the adhesion of bandages to the skin in cases where they won&#39;t stick.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Hydrocortisone cream can be used to reduce itching caused by rashes.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Aloe vera is a natural remedy for treating burns.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Dental repair paste is a temporary solution for filling a chipped tooth.</li>
							</ul>

							<p>It&#39;s important to have an adequate supply of prescription medications for family members who require them for chronic conditions. You will need to consult with your physician to obtain a prescription for these medications. In some cases, you may need to travel to Mexico to purchase them over-the-counter at pharmacies.</p>

							<p>Similarly, while it&#39;s essential to use antibiotics judiciously, it&#39;s crucial to have them on hand in case of a severe infection. Infections can be life-threatening, and timely treatment with antibiotics can save lives. If you&#39;re unable to travel to Mexico to purchase antibiotics, some veterinary medications are identical to human antibiotics, manufactured in the same factories but sold under different names and packaging.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>THE IMPORTANCE OF PROPER SANITATION</strong></p>

							<p>Personal hygiene is often thought of as a way to avoid offending others, but its role in disease prevention is equally crucial. The importance of personal hygiene and sanitation gained recognition with the development of the germ theory of disease in the mid to late 1800s. Prior to that, people paid little attention to bathing or hand-washing.</p>

							<p>Most of the unpleasant odors that we seek to eliminate through bathing are caused by bacteria on our bodies and the substances they produce. Thus, maintaining personal hygiene is necessary for maintaining sanitation. However, we tend not to think of it this way.</p>

							<p>Disasters and epidemics often coincide due to the proliferation of disease-carrying pests, such as rodents and flies, and the general lack of hygiene. In such situations, it can be difficult to maintain cleanliness when water is scarce, let alone to keep one&#39;s home clean.</p>

							<p>Nevertheless, maintaining cleanliness is critical during such times. The challenge is finding ways to stay clean without using excessive amounts of water, particularly potable water.</p>

							<p><strong>Hand Disinfectant</strong></p>

							<p>Using hand sanitizer is generally sufficient for most purposes, as it can effectively reduce the transmission of disease pathogens. These pathogens often enter our bodies through the openings in our face, and are frequently carried by our hands, which come into contact with contaminated surfaces or fluids from sick individuals. Although hand sanitizer may not be able to eliminate all microscopic pathogens, it can effectively kill most of them, thereby significantly reducing the likelihood of infection. Thus, it is important to use hand sanitizer whenever there is uncertainty about the cleanliness of a surface or object.</p>

							<p>To ensure an adequate supply of hand sanitizer, it is advisable to either stockpile it in advance or obtain the necessary ingredients to make it later. However, it is not recommended to rely solely on homemade hand sanitizer or alcoholic beverages, as these may not contain a high enough concentration of alcohol to effectively kill pathogens. In the aftermath of a disaster, finding the required 91% alcohol may prove difficult, underscoring the importance of being prepared ahead of time.</p>

							<p><strong>Water-Saving Bathing Techniques</strong></p>

							<p>We Americans have a bit of an obsession with bathing. We&#39;ve gone from the extreme of only bathing once a week to bathing every day. However, there are many places in the world where people don&#39;t bathe as often as we do.</p>

							<p>The biggest issue with bathing is the amount of water it requires. The average shower uses 10 to 25 gallons of water, and filling a bathtub for bathing takes 35 to 50 gallons. This can be a lot of water to haul from a nearby source or pump by hand from a well.</p>

							<p>Having traveled to Mexico and Colombia, where water is not always abundant, I have seen how people in these areas bathe. They use a five-gallon bucket to carry a couple of gallons of water into the bathroom. Then, they use a small plastic container, like a Cool Whip container, to wet themselves down, lather up, wash their hair (if they choose to do so), and rinse with the same container. Men, who typically have shorter hair, can get clean using less than a gallon of water this way, while women require more due to their longer hair.</p>

							<p>While this method of bathing may not be as satisfying as a long, hot shower, it can still effectively clean your body. Additionally, it is possible to keep yourself clean without washing your hair every day. Depending on how oily your scalp is, you may only need to wash your hair every two or three days.</p>

							<p>It is also important to note that the water used for bathing does not need to be clean enough for drinking. So, if you find yourself in a situation where clean water is scarce, you can still use available water sources for bathing purposes.</p>

							<p><strong>Clothes Washing</strong></p>

							<p>Washing clothes is a significant water-consuming task, particularly when done in a washing machine. However, in a scenario without running water or electricity, using a washing machine is not an option. One possible alternative is to place the clothes in the bottom of the shower and walk on them. But this may prove challenging if only a gallon or two of water is available for bathing.</p>

							<p>A more feasible option is to plug the shower drain, allowing water to accumulate in the tub for clothes washing. Additional water will only be needed for rinsing. Since only a few gallons of water are available at a time, clothes will need to be washed continuously, a little at a time, every time someone takes a bath. Despite the effort, it is still more practical than using up all the water just for laundry purposes.</p>

							<p>Without power, clothes will have to be hung on a clothesline outdoors to dry. It is important to avoid drying them indoors. Sun exposure will not only dry the clothes, but it will also aid in cleaning them by killing bacteria and other harmful pathogens.</p>

							<p><strong>Toilet Matters</strong></p>

							<p>If you are living without access to city water, it is likely that your city&#39;s wastewater system will also be out of order. In such a situation, if you are using the city sewage system, there will be no outlet for the drainage from your home. You will need to find an alternative solution to deal with the water from bathing and washing clothes. Additionally, you will need to find a way to replace your toilet.</p>

							<p>There are a few different options available to you. One of the easiest options is to use a five-gallon bucket toilet. You can purchase toilet seats that are specifically designed for use with a five-gallon bucket, which are ideal for survival situations. By placing a plastic bag inside the bucket to catch the waste, you can seal it and store it until the sewage treatment plant is operational again. To help the waste break down and minimize odors, adding lime (the mineral) to the bag before sealing it can be beneficial.</p>

							

							<p>An alternative approach is to use composting for the waste. Human waste has been utilized as fertilizer in some areas of the world for centuries. Composting toilets are available, which naturally compost human waste. However, if you&#39;re already composting for your garden, you can safely incorporate human and pet waste into the compost, even without a composting toilet.</p>

							<p>In a long-term survival situation, a five-gallon bucket toilet might not be sufficient, except if you&#39;re composting. Eventually, you&#39;ll need to address the issue of waste disposal. This is where outhouses come in handy. Although they may not be pleasant, they provide a secure and private location to deal with your waste.</p>

							<p>It is crucial to carefully select a location for your outhouse. It must be situated at least 100 feet away from any water source to prevent contamination. If you have a well, it&#39;s essential to avoid placing the outhouse near it. Moreover, it should not be situated uphill of any water source as waste from the outhouse could flow downhill and contaminate the water source. Additionally, it&#39;s recommended to keep the outhouse far enough from your house and your neighbors&#39; houses to minimize unpleasant odors.</p>

							<p>To break down the waste and keep odors at bay, adding lime (calcium hydroxide) to the contents of the outhouse is recommended. Lime can usually be purchased at a local feed store. Alternatively, wood ash can be used if lime is not available, though it&#39;s not as effective in eliminating odors. After each use, sprinkle one cup of lime or wood ash around the outhouse to cover the added content.</p>

							<p>For those who have septic systems, these concerns do not apply. A septic tank can last for several years before it needs to be emptied. However, it is important to have the tanks emptied on a regular basis to maximize capacity in the event of a disaster.</p>

							<p><strong>Maintaining a Tidy Living Environment In Your Home</strong></p>

							<p>Keeping your home clean is not only important for aesthetic purposes but also for preventing diseases caused by pests. Dirt and food crumbs are a magnet for pests, and these pests can carry diseases that can be transmitted to humans. Therefore, it&#39;s essential to maintain a clean environment to avoid inviting pests into your home.</p>

							<p>To clean your home, you can reuse the water you used for bathing and washing your clothes, especially for cleaning the floor. Since the water used for cleaning the floor is not clean, using the same water from bathing and washing clothes won&#39;t make much of a difference. It&#39;s important to keep in mind that water conservation is vital during emergency situations.</p>

							<p>Stocking up on cleaning products and sanitizers is an essential part of being prepared for emergencies. You should have enough supplies of cleaning products and rotate them regularly to ensure that they are not expired. It&#39;s also important to stock up on plastic bags to dispose of waste, such as food scraps and used tissues, properly.</p>

							<p>In conclusion, maintaining cleanliness in your home is crucial in preventing the spread of diseases caused by pests. Reusing water and having sufficient stocks of cleaning products and plastic bags are simple yet effective ways to ensure a clean and safe environment during emergencies.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center">&nbsp;</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>PROTECTING YOUR HOME AND FAMILY</strong></p>

							<p>During times of unrest, such as those caused by disasters, crime tends to increase. We&#39;ve all heard about looting and other criminal activities that take place in the wake of natural disasters. In the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina, the situation was so dire that the mayor had to institute a curfew and even confiscate firearms under martial law. While some people might see these measures as necessary, I don&#39;t agree with the mayor&#39;s actions.</p>

							<p>The fact is that crime rates tend to go up during times of crisis for several reasons. For one, law enforcement is often preoccupied with other pressing issues, which gives criminals an opportunity to take advantage of the situation. Additionally, many people may have evacuated their homes, leaving them unguarded and vulnerable to theft. Finally, desperate times may drive people who would not ordinarily break the law to do so in order to obtain the things they need to survive.</p>

							<p>The likelihood of people turning to crime after a disaster is largely dependent on the severity of the disaster and the desperation of the people affected. While some criminals will inevitably take advantage of the situation, ordinary people typically resort to crime only when they are in dire need. In such cases, essential resources are key. However, when people don&#39;t get what they need, there is always a chance that they may turn to violence. Some may band together and attack homes they believe have food, and these groups may be armed and willing to harm others.</p>

							<p>In such situations, relying solely on locks for home security may not be enough. Despite the benefits of locks, they cannot prevent determined intruders from breaking windows or kicking down doors. While there are steps you can take to enhance your home&#39;s security, they are somewhat limited, and defending your home may become necessary.</p>

							<p>You need to be armed and trained to use your guns to defend your home. Choosing the type of gun you want to own is a matter of personal preference, but you don&#39;t need a sniper rifle. Remember that using deadly force is only allowed in self-defense, so shooting someone who is a block away from you could be difficult to justify in court. For home defense, hunting guns are not recommended because they are too long for maneuvering inside your home. A pistol or tactical shotgun, preferably a bullpup design, would be more suitable. Stock up on plenty of ammunition for your chosen guns, with around 1,000 rounds for each caliber of rifle and 300 rounds of shotgun and pistol ammo for each gun.</p>

							<p>Your ability to use a firearm well is more important than the specific caliber or type of firearm you have. Crisis situations can impair your fine motor skills due to the spike in adrenaline, making it harder to maintain trigger control and shoot accurately. This means your shooting ability may be significantly worse during a home invasion, with a higher likelihood of missing your target. The risk of not hitting your target is that the bullet can continue through walls and potentially hit unintended objects or bystanders. Even a 9mm bullet can pass through multiple layers of plywood or brick walls. As the shooter, you are legally responsible for every bullet that leaves your gun, and hitting an innocent bystander can result in arrest and charges such as manslaughter. Therefore, it&#39;s crucial to avoid missing your intended target.</p>

							<p><strong>Practice Makes Perfect</strong></p>

							<p>The key to accuracy in a crisis situation is practice. Shooting accurately is a skill that takes time to master. Once you have achieved accuracy, tactical training can be helpful in teaching you how to maneuver and shoot, choose priority targets, and avoid being shot. It is important to remain calm in order to control adrenaline. Many shooting ranges offer tactical shooting events that are competitive and require you to shoot under pressure. This type of training will help you to overcome the problem with adrenaline and prepare you to protect your home and family. Encouraging your survival team to train and practice is also important for their ability to protect you and your family.</p>

							<p><strong>Secret Hide Out</strong></p>

							<p>Safe rooms are often suggested as a solution to protect your home from attack, but are typically only found in the homes of the wealthy due to their high cost. These rooms are designed to be bulletproof and offer a place for the family to retreat to in times of danger. Safe rooms can be made using various materials, with most utilizing fiberglass or Spectra-shield panels and a specially designed steel door for ballistic protection. Alternatively, a safe room can be made from concrete, but it would require a basement or a cement slab to support the weight of the walls. While safe rooms can provide protection for a limited time, they are not a perfect solution. Without reliable police protection or communication, the family is essentially trapped. It is recommended to include an escape tunnel in the safe room and to store bug out bags and firearms for added security.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>PART 3 - SURVIVING FOR THE LONG-HAUL</strong></p>

							<p>In this discussion, we have primarily focused on short-term survival situations that might last for a few months. Although we have touched on the idea of long-term survival, we have not delved into it in detail. Most preppers prioritize preparing for short-term situations before considering potential long-term scenarios.</p>

							<p>A long-term survival situation can refer to anything that lasts longer than a few months, but from a planning standpoint, it generally means anything that goes beyond a year. Essentially, it&#39;s any situation that lasts longer than the supplies in your stockpile can sustain you. Dealing with long-term survival requires self-sufficiency, which entails being able to grow your food and cater to your needs. Achieving this level of self-sufficiency can take a year or more, and growing all your food can even take several years.</p>

							<p>As Napoleon is quoted as saying, &quot;Then we should begin immediately&quot; when told his plan to plant trees beside all of France&#39;s major roads so that his troops could march in the shade. Although we should prioritize some other things first, it&#39;s wise to start preparing for long-term survival when possible. Some of the things we can do, such as growing our food, can even be beneficial in the present, even without any disaster happening.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center">&nbsp;<strong>WHAT IS BUGGING IN/OUT? WHICH IS BETTER</strong></p>

							<p>When facing a survival situation, one of the biggest questions to consider is whether to bug out or bug in. In the past, the common philosophy was to bug out in response to a thermonuclear war. However, times have changed, and threats have evolved. While there is still a nuclear threat, it is expected to manifest as an EMP attack. In such a case, it may not be necessary to leave your home, and your chances of survival may be better if you stay home. Your home can act as a shelter for you and your family, and it also houses your stockpile of food and other supplies. However, there may come a time when you have to leave your home, as was the case for the people of Southeast Houston during Hurricane Harvey or the people of Paradise, California, during the Camp Fire. When to bug out is a unique decision based on each situation. City dwellers will likely need to bug out sooner than those living in rural areas.</p>

							<p>In the end, the decision to bug out or bug in should be based on what will give your family the greatest chance of survival. Bugging in is often the preferred option for most people as it is easier to survive in the safety of your own home, rather than trying to survive in the wilderness. However, if you own a cabin in the woods that has been prepared as a survival retreat, your chances of survival may be greater there. It&#39;s important to note that it&#39;s not advisable to rely on living off the land in a bug out scenario, as it&#39;s much harder to survive that way than most people realize. While it may have been possible in the past with more wild game and a lower human population, it&#39;s much more challenging today. Having a bug out plan is still important, but it&#39;s crucial to have a specific location in mind that can provide you with the necessary safety and supplies to survive.</p>

							<p><strong>Preparing Your Bug Out Bag</strong></p>

							<p>Being prepared for a potential bug out situation is crucial. This means having a bug out bag ready to go, which will provide you with the necessary survival gear and enough food to get you from your home to your survival retreat. Different people may have different ideas about what should be in their bug out bag, as it is a personal item that needs to be tailored to individual needs, the climate they are dealing with, and their own level of survival knowledge. Carrying gear that you don&#39;t know how to use is not helpful.</p>

							<p>At a minimum, a bug out bag should be able to provide the basic survival priorities that were discussed in chapter one. The website,<a href="http://www.ready.gov/" style="text-decoration:none"> <span style="color:#1155cc"><u>www.Ready.gov</u></a>, recommends that many people stock three days of mostly freeze-dried food in their bags. However, it is better to have more food than that. At a minimum, there should be enough food to get you to your survival retreat, where you should have a cache of food.</p>

