							<p>However, one essential thing that is missing from my bug out bag is a first-aid kit. I have intentionally left it out because I plan to grab the first-aid kit that I keep in the trunk of my car. This kit is housed in a bag designed for a travel shave kit and contains enough supplies to take care of most trauma wounds.</p>

							<p><strong>Survival Hideout</strong></p>

							<p>There are some people who are choosing to avoid the need to bug out by buying land in the countryside and building their own home or survival retreat there. While some real estate companies are selling land specifically for preppers who want to live off the grid, this option requires a lot of money and a career change to work from the remote home.</p>

							<p>For those who can&#39;t afford to buy a cabin in the woods or live off the grid, there are other options. One such option is to find someone who lives outside of town and use their land as a base for a survival team. Alternatively, you could buy a piece of land in joint tenancy with your survival team to bring everyone together in one place.</p>

							<p>If these options aren&#39;t possible, finding a rural community where you could bug out to in case of a disaster is the next best option. However, it&#39;s important to integrate yourself into the community and build relationships with the locals before a disaster strikes. Renting a storage space and building a supply cache in the community can help establish your presence and give you a claim to the town, even if the roads are blocked.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>BARTERING/TRADING</strong></p>

							<p>Building a stockpile is a great way to ensure you have what you need during a disaster, but it&#39;s impossible to predict every situation and prepare perfectly. Even with years of studying and preparing to survive, there will always be things you miss, as I did during the Coronavirus pandemic.</p>

							<p>In a major disaster, cash money will likely lose its value. It may still be accepted initially, but as society breaks down, fewer places will accept it without a fully functioning government to back it up. A financial collapse, such as the one in Argentina in 1999, can also render money virtually worthless, leading people to turn to bartering.</p>

							<p>Bartering becomes a norm whenever people lose confidence in their government&#39;s ability to maintain the value of their currency. In such cases, it&#39;s important to have a stock of barter goods that you can use. These can be the same sorts of food and supplies you&#39;ve stockpiled for your family.</p>

							<p>However, it&#39;s important not to take from your family&#39;s stockpile to have trade goods. Instead, you should establish a separate stock of things you&#39;ll use for that purpose, over and above your family&#39;s needs. Additionally, you may want to stockpile a few things strictly for bartering, such as tobacco, alcohol, or coffee. These items are in high demand and can be valuable trade goods.</p>

