							<p><strong>How To Barter Like A Pro</strong></p>

							<p>In times of crisis, bartering can be dangerous and it&#39;s important to take precautions. To mitigate the danger, it&#39;s recommended not to do bartering at home unless it&#39;s with someone you already know. This is to prevent giving the impression that you have items at home that others might need, which could invite attacks. It&#39;s also advisable to take only what you need for bartering and not to take too much with you.</p>

							<p>Security is the number one watchword when bartering. It&#39;s recommended to go to a marketplace where other traders are present as this will offer some security. However, it&#39;s still important to take security measures from your own team. It&#39;s best to take security and have them watch from a short distance away so that nobody knows they are with you. This way, they can offer support and surprise attackers if someone tries to rob you. It&#39;s also important to take a circuitous route when going to and from the marketplace to ensure you&#39;re not followed, as someone might try to find out where you live.</p>

							<p>Fairness in your dealings with others is also essential. Even though you have the advantage, it&#39;s important not to press it too far. Resentment from people you&#39;re trading with could motivate them to become enemies instead of repeat customers. It&#39;s important to find a balance between what you think items are worth and what they think they&#39;re worth. The best trade is one in which both parties feel like they got a good deal. While not always possible, it&#39;s something to strive for.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>SUSTAINABLE FOOD, SUSTAINABLE YOU!</strong></p>

							<p>It&#39;s not practical to stockpile enough food for an indefinite period of time, as even a 10-year supply is nearly impossible. Most people limit their stockpiles to about a year and focus on growing their own food instead. This approach is consistent with the history of human civilization, where farming eventually replaced hunting and gathering because it was more efficient. With farming, you can usually raise more food than you can hunt or gather.</p>

							<p>You don&#39;t need to start a full-blown farm to achieve this goal. Instead, you can focus on large-scale gardening and raising small animals. You may have read an article about someone who grew all their food in their backyard, and if they can do it, so can you.</p>

							<p>Some people claim that you can sustain yourself with a small vegetable garden, such as the concept of a &quot;four-foot garden&quot; that uses vertical gardening. However, it&#39;s not realistic to believe that such a small area can provide enough food for your needs. To grow all your own food, you&#39;ll likely need your entire backyard, and possibly even your front yard too.</p>

							<p>The key to success is starting small and gradually building your garden. If you&#39;re new to gardening, it takes time to learn how to grow plants effectively. I know this from personal experience, as I had to learn the hard way.</p>

							<p>Raised beds are often more effective than traditional gardening for most people. There are several reasons for this, but the main one is that you can grow more food in a raised bed compared to planting in rows. Additionally, you use less seed because you plant more intentionally, rather than just scattering seeds in a row.</p>

							<p>Here&#39;s an example: let&#39;s say you want to plant carrots. The seed packet may recommend planting them two inches apart. If you&#39;re planting them in rows, you would do that, but the rows would be a foot apart to leave space for walking. This wastes a lot of space. However, with a raised bed garden, you can plant the seeds two inches apart and put the rows two inches apart, allowing you to have six times as many rows of carrots in the same space.</p>

							<p>This concept can be applied even more effectively in other areas. Consider planting tomato plants, which typically require two feet of space between each plant. In a raised bed, you can optimize the space by planting complementary crops such as herbs, cucumbers, celery, onions, peas, or squash in the gaps between the tomato plants.</p>

							<p>Admittedly, creating pathways between the garden beds may reduce some space, but the benefits outweigh the drawbacks. With careful planning, the paths between the planting beds don&#39;t have to be very wide, and you can add ledges to the edges of your beds, providing a place to sit or keep your gardening tools while you work.</p>

							<p>Using raised beds has another crucial advantage, and that is the quality of the soil. Soil is the foundation of any successful garden as it provides essential nutrients and water to the plants. However, many of us have poor soil in our yards. By installing raised beds, you are compelled to bring in soil, and it&#39;s an opportunity to invest in good quality soil. This investment will pay off by yielding a bountiful harvest from your garden.</p>

							<p>When it comes to constructing the beds, you have various options. While I&#39;ve seen creative uses of old bathtubs, used tires, and milk jugs for planting, it&#39;s best to use treated lumber to create proper planting beds. This allows for efficient use of space, even though it may come at a slightly higher cost. Another option is using brick, but that requires additional effort.</p>

							<p>Don&#39;t forget to consider fruit trees in your garden planning. Keep in mind that not all types of fruit trees thrive in all climates. You&#39;ll need to carefully select trees that are suitable for your area. Some fruit trees require a certain number of freezing days to produce fruit, while others may not tolerate freezing temperatures. Consult with your local nursery to determine which fruit trees are best suited for your region.</p>

							<p><strong>Maximizing The Potential Of Your Garden</strong></p>

							<p>To maximize your garden&#39;s potential, it&#39;s essential to provide your plants with the appropriate care, including adequate nutrients and water. I recommend using an electronic moisture meter to monitor watering, but as you gain experience, you may be able to rely on your instincts. Remember, you don&#39;t need to use purified water; rainwater, stream or canal water, and even greywater from your home can be used for your garden, as plants aren&#39;t very particular about their water source.</p>

							<p>During normal times, most people prefer to use chemical fertilizers to &quot;feed&quot; their gardens. However, the writer prefers natural fertilizers, as they are more readily available during times of crisis. Composting is a great way to recycle garden scraps and table scraps into fertilizer for your garden. Composting breaks down plant fibers, releasing nutrients back into the soil. You can also add human or animal waste to your compost. Worms and bacteria do the actual work of breaking down the compost, which can take several months.</p>

							<p>It&#39;s recommended that compost should be added to your garden after harvest time, before winter sets in. This will give the worms time to work the compost into the soil, which will help prepare the garden beds for the next spring. During the growing season, some plants may need additional fertilization, which can be done with other types of fertilizers. Fish emulsion is one of the best fertilizers available and can be easily made at home. Collect leftovers from fish, chop them up fine with a blender, put them in a gallon jar of water, and set it in the sun. Shake the emulsion every few days for a month while the bacteria break it down.</p>

							<p>Fish emulsion is a potent fertilizer, so only a small amount is needed. However, be warned that it doesn&#39;t smell very good when you open the container.</p>

							<p>Using mycorrhizal fungi in your garden can be a great addition aside from fertilizers. This type of fungi forms a symbiotic relationship with the plant by attaching itself to the roots. In this way, both the plant and the fungi can help each other out. The fungi acts as an extension of the roots by bringing nutrients and water to the plant while the plant provides nutrients to the fungi.</p>

							<p>Initially, I used mycorrhizal fungi for my lawn in an area where I had difficulty growing grass. The grass had been cut too low and had been burned by the hot summer sun. Despite trying every other option, I decided to give the fungi a try. Within three weeks, the lawn was growing better in that spot than anywhere else. After experiencing its success in my lawn, I incorporated mycorrhizal fungi into my garden. It helped my plants grow faster and produce larger fruit.</p>

							<p><strong>Buy The Right Garden Seed</strong></p>

							<p>When purchasing seeds for your garden, it is important to select the appropriate type. This goes beyond simply choosing between carrots or tomatoes; you need to consider the specific variety of carrots or tomatoes. There are three primary classifications of seeds:</p>

							<p><strong>Heirloom seed</strong> refers to the original plant seed or seed that has been bred. These plants produce seeds that will grow the next year&#39;s crop.</p>

							<p><strong>Hybrid seed</strong> refers to artificially mixed strains of plants. These plants produce seeds that will grow, but the seed won&#39;t be the same thing as the parent plant.</p>

							<p><strong>GMO seed</strong> refers to genetically modified plants created in a laboratory. These plants produce sterile seeds, which won&#39;t grow.</p>

							<p>To ensure sustainability in a survival garden, it is advisable to use only heirloom seeds that produce plants whose seeds can be harvested and replanted the following year.</p>

							<p><strong>Protein Food</strong><br />
							Although growing vegetables is important for survival, it doesn&#39;t provide animal protein which is essential for a balanced diet. Depending on your location, you may need to raise animals to fulfill this need. However, in urban areas, it can be difficult to raise larger animals such as cattle, so your options may be limited.</p>

							<p><strong>Poultry</strong></p>

							<p>Raising chickens can be a simple solution for animal protein, as they are omnivorous and can eat almost anything. However, if you live in the city, your options may be limited. Generally, you can keep a few birds in your backyard, but roosters are usually not allowed due to noise restrictions. It is recommended to choose layer chickens that are bred to lay eggs rather than fryers bred for cooking. Layers will start providing eggs in about six months and will lay eggs two out of every three days. Therefore, six layer chickens can provide a family of four with one egg per person per day.</p>

							<p><strong>Bunnies</strong></p>

							<p>Bunnies reproduce rapidly and mature fast, making them a convenient source of protein. They can be nourished with vegetable scraps from your garden, which makes feeding them easy and cost-effective. If you don&#39;t have dogs, you could allow them to roam freely, but you must have a sturdy fence around your garden.</p>

							<p><strong>Seafood</strong></p>

							<p>Raising fish is a cost-effective and effortless process, especially if you choose tilapia. Tilapia fish can grow in any tank and clean the algae off the walls. By setting up a worm farm, you can produce enough food for your tilapia fish to eat. However, you should be cautious when selecting other types of fish since some require more space or the growing of feed fish. This can be more challenging than worm farming and will take up more space.</p>

							<p><strong>Food Preservation</strong></p>

							<p>To ensure that the food you grow is not wasted, it is crucial to learn how to preserve it. Eventually, the goal should be to produce enough food for your family&#39;s needs, whether for present or future times of crisis. This means that you need to know how to prevent spoilage of your harvest.</p>

							<p>Although there are various ways to preserve food, particularly for meat, which is the most difficult, there are three primary techniques that you should have at your disposal:</p>

							<ol>
								<li style="list-style-type:decimal">Root Cellar - People used to store their food underground in root cellars before refrigeration or ice boxes. This method provides a consistent temperature of around 55&deg;F, which is cool enough to keep vegetables, especially root vegetables, from spoiling.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:decimal">Canning - This is probably the best means of preserving wet food. The process of canning kills any bacteria in the food and seals it in a container, keeping bacteria, rodents, and insects out. Canning meat is more complex than canning vegetables, requiring a pressure canner, but the reusable jars make it a worthwhile investment.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:decimal">Dehydrating - Dehydration is one of the oldest forms of food preservation, with dried grains found in the tombs of the pharaohs. Dehydration is particularly useful for drying vegetables and meat, which can be easily rehydrated for use in soups.</li>
							</ol>

							<p>It&#39;s worth noting that these preservation methods were used long before the advent of modern technology, including electricity. Therefore, they are particularly well-suited for situations where the power grid is down.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>SUSTAINABLE ENERGY</strong></p>

							<p>Let&#39;s be honest, modern society heavily relies on electricity. From our daily gadgets&nbsp;to home appliances, electricity powers many things we use regularly. While we can&nbsp;technically survive without electricity, life would be much more convenient with it.&nbsp;You may hear people talking about going &quot;off-grid&quot; and generating all their own&nbsp;electricity. However, this is an extremely expensive undertaking. Don&#39;t fall for&nbsp;advertisements that claim you can switch to 100% solar power and never pay the&nbsp;power company again. While it&#39;s possible to generate enough electricity to sustain&nbsp;yourself, these advertisements can be misleading, and you&#39;ll likely still need to buy&nbsp;some electricity, which could cost more than they imply.</p>

							<p>A few years ago, I explored the idea of switching to 100% solar power, but was deterred by the initial cost of $60,000. The solar company presented me with a plan where I would buy enough solar panels to cover my average energy consumption, and then pay off the panels over a few years. The excess energy I produced would be sold to the power company and I could buy more when needed. However, there were a few issues with this plan. First, the power company would buy my electricity at wholesale prices but sell it back to me at retail prices. Additionally, solar panels only produce optimal energy for about eight hours per day, and require precise installation to ensure they are facing the sun, which is not always guaranteed by the installation company.</p>

							<p>Despite these issues, solar power can still be a viable means of producing electricity. It is simply important to avoid the big solar companies and their questionable deals.</p>

							<p>Although there are various methods of generating electricity, the most feasible options for home use are solar and wind power. One of the benefits of both of these methods is that they use renewable resources. However, it&#39;s important to note that producing the same amount of electricity as you currently use is unlikely, unless you&#39;re willing to invest a significant amount of money. Those who are successful in going off-grid tend to significantly reduce their electrical usage, with some individuals even eliminating their reliance on electricity entirely. It is possible to generate enough electricity using these methods, but it requires a significant amount of planning and adjustment to lifestyle.</p>

							<p>The main issue with solar power is that each panel generates a relatively small amount of electricity. To produce a significant amount of power, a large number of panels are needed. Moreover, the power generated by solar panels is intended for charging 12-volt DC batteries, while most home appliances require 120-volt AC power. In order to convert the 12 volts from the panels to 120 volts, the wattage output must be reduced by a factor of 10. Thus, if an 80-watt solar panel is used, the resulting power output would only be 8 watts at 120 volts, which is not much.</p>

							<p>Wind power is a more cost-effective option, providing greater power output per dollar spent, assuming that there is sufficient wind. Most wind turbines do not start producing usable electricity until wind speeds reach 10 MPH or more. Therefore, unless you have consistent winds of at least 10 MPH, wind turbines may not be a worthwhile investment.</p>

							<p>Since both wind and solar power are intermittent, the best course of action for most people is to invest in both as they are able. This way, they can ensure that they have at least some electrical power at all times. While it may not be enough to power everything, it will be sufficient for some essential appliances.</p>

							<p>It is important to note that the electrical power generated by solar or wind should not be used directly to power the appliances you need. Instead, it should be used to charge a battery bank. A battery bank is essentially a group of deep cycle batteries, similar to car batteries but designed to store more power, connected together in parallel. The more batteries you have, the more power you can store. To charge the batteries, you&#39;ll need a solar charge controller, which acts as a 12 volt DC battery charger. You&#39;ll also need a voltage inverter to boost the power to 120 volt AC, allowing you to use it when you need it.</p>

							<p>Calculating how many solar panels and batteries you need can be complex, but the basic idea is that you will need a lot of both to power any appliances. Even one solar panel and one battery can be used to charge your phone, tablet, and operate a radio. A slightly larger system could provide minimal lighting, especially if you use 12 volt LED lights. With a bigger system, you could run an energy-efficient refrigerator. However, if you want to light your whole home, run your furnace, or use your air conditioner, you will need a much larger system.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>ALTERNATIVE WAYS OF COMMUNICATION WITHOUT USING THE INTERNET</strong></p>

							<p>Most forms of communication today rely on electricity, including print media which is produced on presses powered by electricity. The internet, which is the primary communication method today, is entirely electronic.</p>

							<p>But what happens when the power goes out? Typically, there is little to no communication for a few days. However, regulations require phone companies, internet service providers, and radio stations to have backup generators that kick in after UPS systems run out of battery power.</p>

							<p>The duration of continued communication depends on the amount of fuel available for these generators. In the event that the generators run out of fuel, refueling trucks may not be able to reach them, resulting in a complete communication blackout.</p>

							<p>During such a blackout, people will be unable to contact loved ones or obtain news. Alternative communication methods will be necessary.</p>

							<p><strong>Walkie Talkies</strong></p>

							<p>If you need to communicate over short distances, business-band walkie-talkies are a good option to consider. There are many brands available, but Motorola is one of the most popular. It&#39;s important to make sure the radios you choose have a range that meets your needs. Be cautious when reading the range stated in the product literature, as it&#39;s usually under ideal circumstances. It&#39;s wise to purchase radios with a longer range than you need and test them to ensure they are sufficient.</p>

							<p>These radios are powered by AA batteries, so it&#39;s a good idea to stock up on them. You may also want to consider rechargeable batteries, but keep in mind that they have a lower voltage than alkaline batteries, which means they will run out of power more quickly.</p>

							<p><strong>Amateur Radios</strong></p>

							<p>Obtaining a Ham Radio license is considered the ultimate in communication, as it offers some of the most reliable means of communication in the world. Many people believe that obtaining a Ham Radio license is difficult, but it has become much easier since the FCC dropped the requirement of learning Morse code to obtain a license. Instead, you must pass a test on radio propagation theory and regulations. Ham Radio operators in most cities offer classes to help you prepare for the test and provide the testing as well.</p>

							<p>Ham Radio operators are available in almost every country and have managed to get news out even during the worst times of crisis. For instance, when Admiral Byrd led his expedition to the South Pole, it was a Ham Radio operator who managed to stay in contact with him, much to the embarrassment of the Navy. During times of war, Ham Radio operators have been the means by which servicemen stationed abroad could talk to their families.</p>

							<p>Although the internet has replaced much of what the worldwide network of Hams used to do in modern times, the network is still in existence. In case other means of communication fail, Hams will still be operational, provided you have the equipment to communicate with them or listen in.</p>

							<p><strong>High Frequency Radio</strong><br />
							To tune into Ham Radio, one only needs a shortwave radio, with no need for a license for receiving. Thus, adding a shortwave radio to your survival kit or bug out bag is perfectly fine. However, during emergencies, reception may be erratic and locating a particular broadcast may require a lot of searching. To address this, it would be best to invest in a high-quality scanning radio, despite the higher cost. Such radios are easy to use and would prove to be a valuable addition to your gear.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center">&nbsp;</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>WHAT IF MEDICINE IS NOT AVAILABLE?</strong></p>

							<p>In Section 2, Chapter 12, I provided recommendations for creating a family first-aid kit and suggested stocking it with certain medicines. However, what happens if the survival situation extends beyond the availability of your medicines and there are no replacements to be found? This is where herbal medicine comes in.</p>

							<p>Herbal medicine has been the foundation of modern medicine. In fact, many of our current pharmaceuticals are either synthetic versions of naturally occurring substances or these substances harvested and purified for medicinal use. Although herbal medicine lacks the purification process available to large pharmaceutical companies, it does not mean that they are not effective. In fact, some herbal medicines are excellent and can be relied upon when conventional medicine is not available.</p>

							<p>I want to clarify one thing about herbal medicine. There are many fads that are marketed as herbal medicine, but that&#39;s not what I&#39;m referring to. These fads make grand claims about being a cure-all for various ailments, much like the snake oil sold 150 years ago. They come and go, and they are not based on the longstanding wisdom and knowledge of herbal medicine that has been passed down for centuries.</p>

							<p>This wisdom has revealed that certain plants contain substances with medicinal properties. In fact, this knowledge gave rise to the modern pharmaceutical industry, which interestingly enough, often tries to discredit herbal medicine. Nonetheless, herbal medicine is still worth exploring.</p>

							<p>I am by no means an expert on herbal medicine, but I can offer a few tips. I suggest that you study this field further if you find it interesting. I am currently studying it myself in order to increase my own knowledge.</p>

							

							<p><strong>Eggs </strong>have high calcium in the shell, great for gardening and for treating leg cramps. The membrane inside the eggshell can be used as a natural bandage, sticking to the skin.</p>

							<p><strong>Spider&#39;s webs</strong> make excellent bandaging material, absorb blood, promote clotting, and stick to the skin.</p>

							<p><strong>White vinegar</strong> constricts arteries, helping to slow bleeding and promote clotting, and also functions as an antiseptic. Apple cider vinegar is an excellent antifungal, useful for treating scalp and skin irritations.</p>

							<p>Tea Tree Oil - This natural oil has numerous medicinal properties, such as analgesic, antibacterial, antifungal, antiviral, antimicrobial, anti-inflammatory, and antiseptic effects.</p>

							<p><strong>Garlic</strong> is a versatile herb that functions as an antibiotic, antiviral, and antifungal. It can be applied topically or ingested.</p>

							<p><strong>Turmeric</strong> is known for its healing properties, such as helping with rheumatoid arthritis, skin cancer, small pox, chicken pox, healing of wounds, liver ailments, and urinary tract infections. It can be taken with garlic.</p>

							<p><strong>Cayenne pepper</strong> is an effective antibacterial and antifungal that also helps with healing. It can be used topically or mixed with water to lower blood pressure.</p>

							<p><strong>Salicin</strong> substance is similar to aspirin and can be found in jasmine, beans, peas, clover, and the inner bark of the willow tree.</p>

							<p><strong>Pain Relievers Plants</strong> such as turmeric, ginger, cat&#39;s claw, aloe vera, and wild lettuce can all help with pain relief. Wild lettuce has been compared to naturally-occurring morphine.</p>

							

							<p>There are numerous herbal medicines in nature that can be used for a variety of purposes. The most common way to take them is by making teas, but they can also be made into capsules, tinctures, and salves. It is important to find multi-purpose mixtures of herbal medicines that cover the types of situations that you are most likely to encounter and plant the necessary plants in your garden. It is best to start harvesting and preparing medicines now so that you will be familiar with using herbal medicine when the need arises.</p>

							<p>This is especially important for treating chronic conditions. For example, cayenne pepper can be useful for treating high blood pressure, which affects nearly half of the adult population. Turmeric can also be useful for treating rheumatoid arthritis. Having alternatives for these chronic conditions could be lifesaving in a post-disaster situation where medicines are difficult to come by.</p>

							<p><strong>Be Proactive</strong></p>

							<p>It&#39;s important to address any chronic health problems before a disaster strikes. Many chronic diseases, like type II diabetes and high blood pressure, are caused by poor diet and lack of exercise. Losing weight and staying active can help prevent or manage these conditions without relying on medication.</p>

							<p>Regular exercise is an essential part of preparation for survival situations. Our sedentary lifestyle leaves us ill-equipped for physical tasks, making it challenging to perform required survival tasks that require strength and stamina. For example, splitting wood is a demanding job that can take half a day or more. If you need to heat your home with wood, you may find yourself in a situation where you have to do it, so it&#39;s crucial to be physically prepared.</p>

							<p>It&#39;s also important to address any medical issues that require surgery or treatment. In a post-disaster world, surgeries like knee replacements won&#39;t be possible, even if the surgeon is available. It&#39;s better to take care of any medical issues that require surgery now, rather than wait until it&#39;s too late.</p>

							<p>In conclusion, it&#39;s best to be proactive about our health and physical condition. Taking care of chronic problems now can save us from a lot of pain and suffering in the future. By prioritizing our health and preparing ourselves physically, we&#39;ll be better equipped to face any survival situation that comes our way.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>SURVIVING THE WILDERNESS</strong></p>

							<p>This book primarily focused on urban survival, which is a likely scenario for most of us. However, wilderness survival is also a possibility, such as when bugging out or when stranded in the wilderness due to a broken-down car. In such situations, having the appropriate equipment is crucial to survival.</p>

							<p>The first step in surviving any wilderness scenario is having the right equipment at your disposal. If you don&#39;t already have a bug out bag in your car, it&#39;s recommended that you keep something similar on hand. The author keeps extensive emergency bags in the trunks of all their vehicles, which can be used not only for survival situations but also for everyday problems. Although these emergency bags don&#39;t contain food or clothing like a bug out bag, they do have almost everything else that you would need in a survival situation.</p>

							<p>If you want to be prepared for basic survival situations, you should have at least these items with you:</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">A knife for cutting and preparing food or shelter.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">A fire starter to create warmth, light and cook food.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">A water bottle made of stainless steel to carry and store water.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">A rain poncho to protect you from the elements and stay dry.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Emergency blankets to keep you warm when it&#39;s cold or wet.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">A water filter to purify water from any source.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">A flashlight with extra batteries to provide light during nighttime or low-light situations.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">A small first-aid kit for treating injuries or wounds.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Duct tape which can be used for fixing and patching various items.</li>
							</ul>

							<p>If you find yourself lost in the woods and potentially injured, you may be in a survival situation. In this case, what should you do? Ideally, you would have informed someone of where you were going and when you expected to return. This way, if you don&#39;t come back, they can contact the authorities to begin a search and rescue operation.</p>

							<p>Given this, your best course of action may be to stay where you are rather than attempting to find your way out on your own. This is particularly true if you are injured or otherwise unable to navigate effectively. By staying in one place, you increase the likelihood that search and rescue teams will be able to locate you. In the meantime, you should focus on conserving your energy and staying hydrated. If you have the necessary supplies, you can build a shelter and start a fire to keep warm. If you do not have these items, you should prioritize finding or creating them. Above all, remain calm and avoid taking unnecessary risks that could make your situation worse.</p>

							<p>ssuming you didn&#39;t inform anyone of your whereabouts and you&#39;re lost in the wilderness, your only option is to make your way back to civilization. In such a scenario, if the GPS on your phone isn&#39;t working and you&#39;re unsure of your location, heading downhill is the best course of action. Typically, roads are situated in valleys and following them will eventually lead you to civilization. However, it&#39;s advisable not to travel at night. Traveling in the wilderness during the night increases your chances of hypothermia, and it&#39;s also hazardous due to the potential for accidents.</p>

							<p>Please note that hypothermia can occur even in temperatures that are not particularly cold. If the temperature outside is below your body temperature of 98.6&deg;F, your body will be losing heat. Additionally, if it&#39;s raining, the wind is blowing, or your clothes get wet, you will likely be losing heat faster than your body can produce it. Your body temperature doesn&#39;t have to drop much before you start experiencing confusion and disorientation, which can make it difficult to take care of yourself in a survival situation.</p>

							<p>To prevent hypothermia, it&#39;s a good idea to stop and set up camp about two hours before sundown. You don&#39;t need a watch or even knowledge of the exact time of sunset to determine when this is - simply lay your hand horizontally on the horizon at arm&#39;s length. Each finger width that the sun is above the horizon represents roughly 15 minutes of daylight left. When the sun is two hand widths above the horizon, it&#39;s time to stop traveling and start preparing your camp.</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Firewood: You&#39;ll need enough firewood to last you through the night. Make sure to gather a sufficient amount before starting a fire.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Starting a fire: Starting a fire is important for warmth, cooking, and to signal for help. Make sure you have the necessary tools to start a fire, such as matches or a lighter, and that you know how to properly build a fire.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Building a shelter: A shelter is important to protect you from the elements and to help regulate your body temperature. You can use natural materials, such as branches and leaves, to construct a shelter, or use a tarp or emergency blanket if you have one.</li>
							</ul>

							<p>When setting up camp, there&#39;s no need to worry about finding a water source as it can be found during the daytime while traveling. It&#39;s not recommended to set up camp near a water source, as it&#39;s also used by animals. However, camping near a water source can deter animals from using it.</p>

							<p><strong>Survival Shelters in the Wilderness</strong></p>

							<p>It is advisable that you have some shelter-building equipment with you, even if you don&#39;t have a tent. However, before using your supplies, it is best to check the resources that nature has to offer. Nature has many things that can provide shelter or partial shelter. Combining them with your equipment can make a comfortable place to spend the night. In the wild, shelter is primarily for protection against wind and rain. If you have these two things covered, you have a good chance of keeping warm enough to survive. A campfire will improve your chances even further.</p>

							<p>What are some natural shelter options to look for in the wild?</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Caves &ndash; natural formations in the earth that can offer shelter, just make sure they are unoccupied before using them.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Rock outcroppings &ndash; areas where rocks protrude from the ground, may not offer full shelter but can provide partial coverage from wind and rain.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Thickets of trees &ndash; dense areas of trees where you can often find small openings to create a shelter.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Overhanging embankments &ndash; cliffs or hills that provide a natural overhang for protection, but be cautious of potential water flow if it rains.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Deadfall tree &ndash; a fallen tree that can be used as the basis for a shelter by clearing out branches underneath.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Large pine tree &ndash; even though the bottom branches may touch the ground, there is often space close to the trunk that can be used for shelter.</li>
							</ul>

							<p>In some instances, natural resources may only offer you partial shelter. To make up for this, you will need to enhance it by using an emergency blanket or poncho to close off gaps or weaving branches to fill in openings. Keep in mind that you&#39;re not trying to create a luxurious accommodation but instead, you&#39;re aiming to protect yourself from the wind and rain.</p>

							<p><strong>Finding Water</strong></p>

							<p>When traveling during the day in the wilderness, finding a source of water is crucial. It is essential to drink at least 64 oz. of water per day, more if it is hot and you are sweating. To find water, traveling downhill is an excellent direction since water always flows downhill. Observing for signs of water as you go, such as cracked mud in very arid areas, can help. Checking the plants can also help since areas with greater green will indicate where water is more likely to occur. Even in arid lands, trees marking a watercourse can be found.</p>

							<p>Intermittent watercourses may still lead to water, and they all lead to streams, rivers, or lakes. Finding a pool or an area of dried, cracked mud, where there was a pool, might produce a seep where there is water. Animal trails can also lead to water since almost all animals need water, and they usually go to water early in the morning and at dusk.</p>

							<p>It is crucial to purify any water found in the wilderness before drinking it. Assume that any water you find is suspect and don&#39;t drink it unless it is purified first. You can purify water using a water filter or boiling it in a water bottle. Stainless steel bottles are recommended since they can be put in the fire to purify water.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>CONCLUSION</strong></p>

							<p>Preparing for a disaster is not just a task, but a lifestyle that needs to be lived. Each section in this book is just a start and can be further explored. As you work through the information, you will find yourself researching deeper and learning more to add to your knowledge. Completing each prepping project will lead to another, making you more self-sufficient and better prepared to face life&#39;s challenges. Even though it is uncertain when you will use this knowledge, it will become an integral part of you.</p>

							<p>Moreover, you will notice a positive change in your way of living. The preparation and knowledge gained will assist you in dealing with daily life challenges, like taking care of your children&#39;s injuries or purifying water. Your family will also benefit from the changes in you.</p>

							<p>This journey has a purpose, so don&#39;t look back. You will become a better person as you gain confidence and understanding. You will be able to reach higher, climb farther, and run faster. So, enjoy the ride!</p>
