				<!-- 6. Beginner's Guide to Self Defence Section-->
				<div class="tab-pane fade" id="tab6" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="nav-6-tab">
					<div class="row">
						<div class="col-12">
							<!-- Section Heading-->
							<h2 class="sub-header-salesperson text-center">
								<span  class="text-danger"> <strong>Beginner's Guide to Self Defence</strong> </span>
							</h2>
							<!-- Icon Divider-->
							<div class="divider-custom">
								<div class="divider-custom-line"></div>
								<div class="divider-custom-icon"><i class="fas fa-star"></i></div>
								<div class="divider-custom-line"></div>
							</div>
							<!-- Section Content-->
							<p><strong>Essentials</strong></p>

							<p>The strategies presented in this book are rooted in Jiu-Jitsu, which has been the foundation of many other martial arts and continues to be used by military and law enforcement personnel worldwide. While the origins of Jiu-Jitsu date back thousands of years, the strategies outlined in this book have been adapted to suit modern-day situations. Although there may be some variations in the execution of these strategies among individuals, they are all easy to learn and can be performed by people of all ages.</p>

							<p>To truly grasp the strategies presented in this book, it is important to repeat and teach them to others. This process allows for a deeper understanding of the concepts and prompts individuals to ask themselves important questions. It is important to take the time to fully absorb the concepts rather than rushing through to learn the next set of strategies.</p>

							<p>The system presented in this book is made up of various concepts that are easier to learn than memorizing a different strategy for each type of attack. Basic hitting and placing techniques are combined with fundamental breakaways to provide a comprehensive understanding of the fundamentals of self-defense. By mastering these primary concepts, individuals will gain a solid foundation in self-defense.</p>

							<p>It&#39;s important to consider that the safety of your environment might change over time. Although you may currently feel safe and don&#39;t see the need for this type of book, the region you live in could be expanding with new people who bring in different thoughts and values. You may also travel for work or leisure to a new area where you are unfamiliar with the surroundings. Therefore, it is always useful to learn some fresh ideas and strategies. By opening your mind and looking at the situation from a wider point of view, you can be better prepared for the unforeseen.</p>

							<p>The strategies presented in this book are designed using Gross Motor Skills, which are basic body movements that are easy to learn and execute. This is a crucial factor to consider when learning self-defense strategies, as they must be simple enough to be performed under pressure.</p>

							<p>To truly internalize and become proficient in these strategies, it is recommended to practice them with family and friends. The more you practice, the more innate they will feel, and you will be better equipped to execute them effectively in real-life situations. It is also helpful to practice in different locations, such as the kitchen, bathroom, living room, or garage, to ensure that you are prepared to defend yourself in any environment.</p>

							<p>If you spend most of your time in small rooms or spaces, it&#39;s important not to limit your practice to the large open space of a gym. Instead, you need to practice in environments that are applicable to you.</p>

							<p>To be more aware of potential threats, it&#39;s helpful to know who your foe might be and learn to recognize their movements, even rituals that are common among certain types of attackers. Women, for instance, are more likely to encounter a different kind of attacker than men. Typically, women are more likely to face male attackers like muggers or rapists as opposed to other women.</p>

							<p>Understanding the attacker increases the likelihood of defeating them. Many of these individuals are deceptive, and often the bigger the crime, the bigger the deceit. Not all aggressors fit the stereotype of &quot;The Bad Guy,&quot; and domestic violence is unfortunately a common occurrence.</p>

							<p>Try not to get caught up in your own little bubble and be aware that there are people outside of your immediate circle. Whether we like it or not, there are people out there whose intentions are not always good. You may never encounter such people, but then again, you may or may have already. It could be at work, at home, on the street, in a bar, or even on the road. Don&#39;t let your guard down, as these are the types of individuals that predators seek.</p>

							<p>Bad things sometimes happen to good people, and it&#39;s important to acknowledge that it could happen to anyone, including you. I&#39;m not saying that it will, but it&#39;s a possibility. We hear about these incidents happening every day, and being aware that it&#39;s out there is a significant step.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>Self-Defense Techniques for Escaping Dangerous Situations</strong></p>

							<p><strong>Escape</strong></p>

							<p>Self-protection is not just about mastering a few defensive tactics; it&#39;s also about incorporating safety measures into our daily routine to enhance our security. Most of it is common sense, while the rest of it is simply a matter of habit. Some things we do without even thinking about them, such as wearing a seatbelt, crossing the street safely, or using a knife properly. In the past, people had to be persuaded to wear seatbelts, but now it&#39;s second nature. This illustrates that repeated behavior can become a habit and ultimately feel like second nature.</p>

							<p><strong>Body Language</strong></p>

							<p>The way you carry yourself, such as looking down, slouching, hiding your hands in your pockets, and making yourself small, sends a message that you are weak and vulnerable. Women are often targeted as easy victims, so it is important to have strong body language to reduce the risk of being targeted. Make eye contact with people in a way that shows you have noticed them (potential criminals are less likely to act if they think they could be identified). When walking, swing your arms and take up space. Strong body language not only affects how others perceive you, but also boosts your own self-confidence. Just like predators in the wild, attackers on the streets do not go after the strongest or most unassailable prey, but rather the weak, injured, or isolated. Avoid putting yourself in situations that increase your vulnerability. Attackers are not looking for a fight, but an easy target, and when faced with fierce resistance, they often give up their attempt.</p>

							<p><strong>Verbal Strategies</strong></p>

							<p>Asserting yourself is an important aspect of taking control of your life. If someone&#39;s behavior is making you feel uncomfortable, upset, or scared, then confront the person. You should identify the behavior, criticize it, and let them know what you want them to do. For instance, you could say, &quot;You&#39;re constantly touching me, and I don&#39;t like it. Stop it.&quot; You should avoid using the word &quot;please&quot; when you&#39;re asserting yourself.</p>

							<p>If someone is bothering you in a public place, make a scene. This will be much more embarrassing for the person than it is for you. Your voice is also a weapon. Yelling will alert others and may startle an attacker. It may also help channel your fear into aggression, so you should scream &quot;NO&quot; loudly from your stomach.</p>

							<p>Trust your instincts. If something seems off, it probably is. For example, if someone is following you and makes you feel uneasy, believe your instinct and take action. You could confront the person, get to safety, call someone for help, or get a weapon ready. A cellular phone is a handy tool to have in case of an emergency. It is not expensive if it&#39;s for emergency use only. You can summon help from anywhere and even use it as a weapon if you know how.</p>

							<p>If a physical confrontation occurs, use your voice. Scream loudly as you strike. This serves multiple purposes. First, you may startle the attacker with a sudden loud scream. Second, you are attracting attention to yourself, and someone might come to your aid. Third, you are producing witnesses who can be useful if you inflict physical harm to the attacker. In self-defense, it may come down to your word versus theirs. If a passerby heard you scream &quot;Let go, let go,&quot; then that becomes evidence. Screaming also tenses up your abdominal region, so if you get hit at the same time, you are less likely to be out of breath.</p>

							<p><strong>Direct Relationship of Space And Danger</strong></p>

							<p>The amount of time you have to react to your aggressor&#39;s movements is directly related to your proximity to them. Therefore, the further away you are, the more time you have to respond. To ensure that you have enough time to react, it is essential to maintain a safe distance that you are comfortable with. If possible, it is also advisable to position yourself behind an obstacle that creates a barrier between you and the other person. It&#39;s important to note that the aggressor has the upper hand when it comes to the action-response cycle because they know when they will strike. However, your brain needs to process their actions, decide how to respond, and send signals to your muscles to move accordingly. This is why it&#39;s crucial to adopt a defensive stance, such as the interview stance, and keep a safe distance.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>Contrasts between Martial Arts and Self-Defense</strong></p>

							<p><strong>Variations</strong></p>

							<p>Traditional martial arts often focus on Kata, which are choreographed sequences of moves and techniques, designed to simulate fighting one or more opponents. These often require speed, power, good balance, and flexibility. While Kata can be a valuable training tool, they provide little assistance in practical modern self-defense situations. Many traditional martial arts don&#39;t prepare you for when an attacker comes in close contact or takes you to the ground, as these techniques may not be allowed under the rules of a particular style. It&#39;s important to remember that in a real-world street fight or assault, anything goes.</p>

							<p>Imagine two athletes facing off against each other in a tournament. They&#39;ve trained for a long time, and they&#39;re in good physical shape. Now, let&#39;s remove the referee and the rules they were there to enforce. Anything goes; the fighters aren&#39;t limited to the same set of moves they&#39;re accustomed to. Let&#39;s take away the gloves, foot pads, headgear, groin protector, and mouthguard. We&#39;ll replace the mat with concrete and add some brick walls. Let&#39;s take away the lighting, too.</p>

							<p>We&#39;ll remove the crowd and anyone else who might have jumped in to break up the fight, leaving one person beaten beyond unconsciousness. Let&#39;s change the environment to a back alley, a kitchen, a bedroom, or even a bar. We&#39;ll provide all the weapons in each of these environments, such as glass, steel bars, screwdrivers, knives, and other items that can be used as weapons. In these situations, a different mentality is required, one that isn&#39;t necessarily covered in a typical martial arts class.</p>

							<p>To effectively defend yourself in a real-world scenario, it&#39;s important to learn techniques that focus on practical self-defense rather than just sport. This includes being aware of your surroundings, identifying potential threats, and learning techniques for dealing with a variety of situations. It&#39;s also crucial to have a mindset that&#39;s focused on survival and not just winning. The techniques taught in self-defense classes are designed to be effective in real-world situations and are often simpler and more direct than traditional martial arts techniques.</p>

							<p>Street encounters often start with a surprise attack, such as a mugging or an attempted rape, rather than a prepared stand-off. Even skilled martial artists can fall apart in such situations due to the required mentality, and techniques that work in a training hall might not be practical on the street, especially in confined spaces. Thus, it is essential to be mentally prepared for a street fight, as well as to train in a way that simulates real-life situations.</p>

							<p>Rather than take chances, it is wise to avoid or break away from potential attackers. Training partners should be asked to stand firm and make it hard to respond with the necessary techniques. It is also important to practice with full-on blows, using padded gear to simulate the force of a real attack. Otherwise, if always pulling punches 2 inches away from hitting the object in training, chances are that one&#39;s innate reaction under pressure might be the same.</p>

							<p>An expert in a specific martial arts style does not necessarily mean they are an authority in self-defense. In some cases, they may be, but the two do not necessarily go hand in hand. Hollywood often glamorizes violent scenes with a hero using a range of fancy strategies against multiple aggressors with various weapons, but the reality is that these situations are often bloody, ghastly, dirty, and end in injury or death. Survivors of such situations might end up with broken bones, facial injuries, or other physical and mental scars that may never fully heal.</p>

							<p><strong>Fear</strong></p>

							<p>Take a moment to consider what causes fear within us. It&#39;s the realization that the person in front of us could cause us serious harm, disfigurement or even death. We have loved ones at home - children, spouses, friends, and others - who are waiting for us, and we may never see them again.</p>

							<p>In such situations, it&#39;s crucial to remind ourselves that we have the right to return home to our loved ones, and this despicable individual should not deny us that right. Our family and friends need us, and we need them, so we must find the courage to face our fear and do what is necessary to protect ourselves and return home safely.</p>

							<p><strong>Getting Home: Doing Whatever It Takes</strong></p>

							<p>If that means sticking your fingers deep into somebody&rsquo;s eyes, then so be it. It&#39;s important to start thinking more about what you will do to protect yourself instead of what your attacker might do to you.</p>

							<p>During an encounter, it is normal to feel a surge of adrenaline, which can often be mistaken for fear, especially if you are not used to it. The body may tremble, legs may feel weak, there may be loss of bowel control, and the mind may go blank. These are all common symptoms of adrenaline as the body prepares itself for fight or flight. However, adrenaline can also give you extra speed and force, so it is there to assist you.</p>

							<p>Always remember that you are worth it! If you are ever assaulted, do not worry about what the attacker might do to you. Instead, focus on learning how to protect yourself, so you can worry more about what you will do to them! Once you have made the decision to fight, there is no holding back. Give it everything you have got.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>Techniques and Tools for Body Posture</strong></p>

							<p><strong>Familiarity Is Important</strong></p>

							<p><strong>When Being Interviewed</strong></p>

							<p>Prior to any physical confrontation, it is important to stand in a comfortable and prepared position. Begin by positioning your feet shoulder-width apart and opening your hands at chest level while tucking your elbows away. Keep a close eye on your aggressor, focusing on their chest to detect any motion from their hands or feet. It is advisable to maintain a distance of at least six feet to provide enough response time. By doing so, you will be in a safer position, alert, and ready to protect yourself. Make sure to keep your elbows tucked away to protect your body, and your hands close to your head so that you can move them quickly to shield your face if necessary.</p>

							<p><strong>When In Defense Mode</strong></p>

							<p>Assume a defensive stance by stepping back with your dominant side, the shoulder and leg on that side moving backwards (for instance, your right side if you are right-handed). This allows you to generate more power with your dominant hand or foot when you strike. Stepping back instead of forward also creates a bit more distance between you and the aggressor, which gives you more time to react. Tuck your chin, keep your hands high to protect your face, and bring your elbows in to protect your ribs. Initially, this posture may feel uncomfortable, so practice it enough times until you feel comfortable. Stagger your legs to widen your base and increase stability, and bend your knees slightly to further enhance your balance. This Defensive Stance provides excellent protection and balance, enabling you to move quickly into striking positions.</p>

							<p><strong>Your Body Is Your Tool</strong></p>

							<p>Don&rsquo;t underestimate the defensive tools that your body naturally has. This includes:</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Fists: Used to punch with force, the fist is a powerful tool for striking an opponent in close combat.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Hands: The hands can be used for striking, blocking, or grabbing an opponent&#39;s limbs. They are versatile tools for both offensive and defensive maneuvers.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">&bull; Fingers: The fingers can be used to poke or jab an opponent&#39;s eyes, throat, or other vulnerable areas. They can also be used for gripping and manipulating an opponent&#39;s limbs.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Head: The head can be used to deliver a powerful headbutt to an opponent&#39;s face, nose, or chin. It can also be used for blocking or deflecting incoming strikes.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Elbows: The elbows can be used to strike an opponent&#39;s head, face, or body with great force. They are also useful for blocking and trapping an opponent&#39;s limbs.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Knees: The knees can be used for striking an opponent&#39;s legs, groin, or body. They are also useful for clinching and controlling an opponent&#39;s movement.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Feet: The feet can be used for striking an opponent with kicks or stomps. They are also useful for controlling distance and movement in a fight.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Butt: The butt can be used for striking an opponent in close combat or for pushing them away. It can also be used for blocking or deflecting incoming strikes.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Hips: The hips can be used for generating power in strikes and throws. They are also useful for pivoting and changing direction quickly in a fight.</li>
							</ul>

							<p>How about target areas? Target these:</p>

							<ul>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Groin: The area between the upper thighs and the lower abdomen, a sensitive area that can cause intense pain when struck.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Eyes: The vulnerable organs located in the eye sockets, striking them can cause temporary blindness, pain and disorientation.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Throat: The front part of the neck, a vulnerable area that can cause breathing difficulties or even death if struck hard.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Solar Plexus: The area located in the upper abdomen between the ribcage and navel, a sensitive area that can cause shortness of breath, pain and discomfort if struck.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Knees: The joints connecting the thigh bone to the lower leg bone, a vulnerable area that can cause instability or immobilization if struck.</li>
								<li style="list-style-type:disc">Instep: The top part of the foot, a vulnerable area that can cause pain and disorientation if struck with a hard object.</li>
							</ul>

							<p>Knowing the vulnerable spots of an attacker is crucial regardless of their size. You can increase the force of your strikes by following specific steps. Additionally, screaming with each strike not only startles the attacker but also alerts people nearby and channels fear into aggressiveness.</p>

							<p>To practice striking, observe potential targets on people while talking to them or simply watching them. Consider the different strikes you can use for each target you have in mind. Remember, when it comes to striking, use whatever works for you, regardless of whether it is from a textbook or not.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>Positioning And Striking</strong></p>

							<p><strong>Increase the Intensity</strong></p>

							<p><strong>Positioning</strong></p>

							<p>Targeting the eyes, nose, throat, solar plexus, groin, Instep, and shins are effective places to begin with, as they are easily accessible and can be targeted with various types of hits. While the groin can be a very effective target, it shouldn&#39;t be the only focus. Men tend to react quickly to groin strikes, so it&#39;s best to save this target for close aggressors. Hits can be made more effective in several ways, such as bracing the target area by using a wall or the floor or confining the individual or limb in place while striking. When striking, aim not just at the target area but about six inches past it. Keeping your strike in contact for a count helps produce the maximum transfer of energy, and hitting with a bigger surface gives a better carry-over of energy. Striking the same target area multiple times can also be effective, and screaming can help center your energy into your strike.</p>

							<p>In general, it&#39;s best to strike with hard to soft or soft to hard techniques. For example, you can use your elbow to strike the ribs, or your knee to strike the femoral area. You can also use your knee to strike the groin or your head to strike the nose. Alternatively, you can use your palms to strike the head. By using this approach, you can generate maximum force and impact, which can help you to defend yourself effectively.</p>

							<p>Punching to the head is not advisable due to the high risk of breaking knuckles and fingers. Moreover, the human head is hard, which makes it difficult to cause significant damage to an attacker with punches. Additionally, there is a risk of contracting infections such as HIV or hepatitis if the attacker&#39;s teeth puncture the knuckles during the punch. Instead, using the palm of the hand to strike can produce the same amount of force with less risk of injury.</p>

							<p>When targeting tender areas, such as pressure points or motor nerve points, full-on strikes may result in permanent damage, and even a 5% hit can have an effect on individuals. Therefore, it is crucial to be careful while hitting such areas. Striking these areas can induce unconsciousness or even shut down that limb.</p>

							<p>However, caution must be exercised while striking the throat or eyes, as it can cause permanent damage or even result in death. These techniques should only be used in real self-defense situations and treated with the utmost care during training.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>Basic Hold Escapes</strong></p>

							<p><strong>What It&rsquo;s All About</strong></p>

							<p>When an aggressor seizes you, it&#39;s essential to go into a defensive posture with your dominant side backwards. This posture will make you more stable and harder for the aggressor to pull you around. A quick strike to a tender area, such as a well-executed shin kick, may end the confrontation on the spot. If not, it will at least act as a distraction, relaxing the aggressor&#39;s grip. Other distractions can include a slap to the head, a poke to the solar plexus, a foot stamp, or even spitting.</p>

							<p>To break free from the hold, pull back on the arm being held and drive your free arm in the opposite direction against the aggressor&#39;s hold. This hit will have twice the force of simply pulling or hitting. By rotating your body, you&#39;re engaging some of your body&#39;s bigger muscle groups against the hold, increasing your chances of getting free. It&#39;s also important to yell as you hit and strike the aggressor in a frail area such as the eyes, throat, groin, solar plexus, or femorals.</p>

							<p>During this process, it&#39;s crucial to give it your all. Your life might depend on it. This will buy you some time, and while the aggressor is preoccupied with whether they will see or breathe again, you can break free and run to safety.</p>

							<p><strong>1st Wrist Hold</strong></p>

							<p>To escape from a wrist grab, start by stepping back into a defensive posture with your dominant side back. Next, draw back the arm that&#39;s being held and use your free arm to strike the aggressor&#39;s arm in the opposite direction, twisting your body to increase the force of the hit. This should help you break free. At the same time, you can also distract the aggressor by hitting them in vulnerable areas like the eyes or throat. If you need to, you can also use other types of hits to disable the aggressor, such as a hard shin kick. Once you&#39;ve created an opening, run to safety as quickly as possible.</p>

							<p><strong>2nd Wrist Hold</strong></p>

							<p>Take a step back into a defensive posture with your dominant side backward. Then, drive your elbows down and turn your wrists somewhat inward as you pull your arms through the aggressor&#39;s thumbs to break free. Follow up with a hard shin kick or target vulnerable areas like the eyes or throat with your fingers before running to safety.</p>

							<p><strong>3rd Wrist Grab Behind</strong></p>

							<p>If an attacker grabs your wrists, step forward into a defensive posture and lift your knee, driving your foot onto their instep. Then, punch your arm out of their grasp and force your elbow back into their solar plexus. After that, quickly run to safety.</p>

							<p><strong>Escaping A Hair Hold</strong></p>

							<p>When the attacker grabs your hair, step forward into a defensive posture. Immediately get a grip on one or two of their digits and bend them backward. Hold the fingers in a lock or break them if possible. If necessary, use a shin kick to disable the attacker and create an opportunity to escape to safety.</p>

							<p><strong>Escaping Bear Hug</strong></p>

							<p>If an attacker seizes you from behind, start by dropping your weight and broadening your stance to increase stability. Then, drive your knuckle joint repeatedly into the back of the aggressor&rsquo;s hands. Next, shoot your head backward into the aggressor&#39;s face. Deliver a hard hit to the groin using an open hand, but also grab, shake, and tear off whatever you can to inflict as much pain as possible. Finally, run to safety.</p>

							<p><strong>Escaping a Head Lock</strong></p>

							<p>When the aggressor tries to grab you, quickly place your hands on the sides of your head to prevent their arm from encircling your neck. Slip beneath their arm as they try to clinch while maintaining a grip on their arm. Continue holding the aggressor&#39;s arm and drive your knee into the nerve-femoralis, which is located a few inches above the knee on the outside of the leg. Push the aggressor away and flee to safety.</p>

							<p><strong>Escaping Punches</strong></p>

							<p>When the aggressor throws punches, take a step back and assume a defensive posture with your hands up in front of your face. The aggressor&#39;s natural response is to punch around your hands in a hook punch or arm-swing. Adjust your elbow to block any punches thrown. Precise alignment of the elbow joint is not necessary as your arms are also part of the block. This block itself can cause significant harm to the aggressor.</p>

							<p style="text-align:center"><strong>Final Thoughts</strong></p>

							<p>When out and about, it&#39;s important to be aware of your surroundings. If you&#39;re walking down the street, pay attention to whether or not someone is following you. If you&#39;re running or walking alone and wearing headphones, your awareness is reduced.</p>

							<p>When you&#39;re out walking, be sure to keep your hands out of your pockets so you&#39;re ready to use them if necessary. Walk confidently, even if you&#39;re not entirely sure where you&#39;re going, and keep your head and eyes up. It&#39;s also a good idea to look at oncoming traffic.</p>

							<p>If you notice a car driving by you repeatedly or someone sitting outside your work or school, don&#39;t hesitate to let someone know. It&#39;s also a good idea to avoid walking in dark alleys or areas, and to always let someone know where you are and what time you expect to be somewhere. If you see something unusual, trust your instincts and avoid it.</p>

							<p>If you&#39;re walking or running alone, don&#39;t wear headphones and be cautious about giving out personal information over the phone. Make eye contact with people you pass to let them know you&#39;ve seen them. If you feel threatened, don&#39;t be afraid to yell for help.</p>

							<p>It&#39;s never a good idea to hitchhike, and be cautious when using ATMs at night. If you carry a handbag with a shoulder strap, be prepared to let it go if it&#39;s snatched. It&#39;s also important to keep a safe distance from strangers who approach you for directions.</p>

							<p>If you&#39;re dropping someone off at their house, make sure they&#39;re safely inside before you drive away. If you see an accident or someone stranded on the side of the road, report it from your cell phone or the nearest phone. Take self-defense classes and practice with friends and loved ones to build confidence in your ability to protect yourself.</p>
